00:11:51.850 --> 00:11:53.390
And in doing that,

00:11:53.390 --> 00:11:55.170
and if you adopt specific behaviors

00:11:55.170 --> 00:11:57.690
at any age of light viewing

00:11:57.690 --> 00:12:00.350
at particular times and particular ways,

00:12:00.350 --> 00:12:02.470
then you can build an emotional system

00:12:02.470 --> 00:12:04.960
that's also reinforced
by your visual system.

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:07.040
So, let's talk about vision.

00:12:07.040 --> 00:12:07.873
What is vision?

00:12:07.873 --> 00:12:10.193
Well, vision starts with the eyes.

00:12:11.240 --> 00:12:15.400
We have no what's called
extraocular light perception.

00:12:15.400 --> 00:12:17.900
While it feels good to
have light on our skin,

00:12:17.900 --> 00:12:19.580
while it feels good to be outside

00:12:19.580 --> 00:12:21.980
in the sunlight for most people,

00:12:21.980 --> 00:12:23.750
the only way that light information

00:12:23.750 --> 00:12:25.860
can get to the cells of your body

00:12:25.860 --> 00:12:27.420
is through these two little goodies

00:12:27.420 --> 00:12:28.253
on the front of your face.

00:12:28.253 --> 00:12:29.220
And for those of you listening,

00:12:29.220 --> 00:12:31.320
I'm just pointing to my eyes.

00:12:31.320 --> 00:12:33.420
As many of you have heard me say before,

00:12:33.420 --> 00:12:34.860
on this and other podcasts,

00:12:34.860 --> 00:12:37.180
your eyes, in particular,
your neural retinas

00:12:37.180 --> 00:12:38.980
are part of your central nervous system.

00:12:38.980 --> 00:12:40.310
They are part of your brain.

00:12:40.310 --> 00:12:42.560
They're the only part of your brain

00:12:42.560 --> 00:12:44.970
that sits outside the cranial vault.

00:12:44.970 --> 00:12:47.260
In other words, you have
two pieces of your brain

00:12:47.260 --> 00:12:49.120
that deliberately got squeezed

00:12:49.120 --> 00:12:50.800
out of the skull during development

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:53.040
and placed in these things
we call eye sockets.

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:56.300
There's a genetic program
for the specific purpose

00:12:56.300 --> 00:12:59.340
of making sure that three
little layers of neurons,

00:12:59.340 --> 00:13:01.720
nerve cells, got squeezed out

00:13:01.720 --> 00:13:04.250
and form what are called
your neural retinas.

00:13:04.250 --> 00:13:06.190
Now, the eyes have a lot
of other goodies in them

00:13:06.190 --> 00:13:07.350
that are very important,

00:13:07.350 --> 00:13:08.183
and those are the goodies

00:13:08.183 --> 00:13:11.370
that we're going to focus on a lot today.

00:13:11.370 --> 00:13:15.660
There's a lens to focus light,
precisely to the retina.

00:13:15.660 --> 00:13:18.483
If you're somebody who requires
eyeglasses or contacts,

00:13:19.490 --> 00:13:22.350
chances are, you don't do that correctly,

00:13:22.350 --> 00:13:24.520
and so, that's why you use other lenses,

00:13:24.520 --> 00:13:26.600
like eyeglasses or contacts.

00:13:26.600 --> 00:13:28.100
There are also other pieces of the eye

00:13:28.100 --> 00:13:30.550
that are designed to
keep the eye lubricated.

00:13:30.550 --> 00:13:32.840
You also have these things
that we call eyelashes.

00:13:32.840 --> 00:13:34.090
Most people don't know this,

00:13:34.090 --> 00:13:37.990
but eyelashes are there to
trigger the blink reflex

00:13:37.990 --> 00:13:40.220
if a piece of dust or something
gets in front of your eye.

00:13:40.220 --> 00:13:42.333
It's a beautiful adaptation of nature.

00:13:43.170 --> 00:13:44.910
They aren't just aesthetically nice.

00:13:44.910 --> 00:13:46.950
Costello happens to have
very long eyelashes.

00:13:46.950 --> 00:13:49.320
He gets compliments
about this all the time.

00:13:49.320 --> 00:13:50.770
Maybe you have long eyelashes.

00:13:50.770 --> 00:13:52.600
I don't have particularly long eyelashes.

00:13:52.600 --> 00:13:54.300
But the eyelashes are there,

00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:56.250
so that if a piece of dust or something

00:13:56.250 --> 00:13:57.880
starts to head towards the cornea,

00:13:57.880 --> 00:13:59.690
the eye blinks very, very fast.

00:13:59.690 --> 00:14:03.840
It's the fastest reflex you
own is your eye blink reflex.

00:14:03.840 --> 00:14:06.160
We also have these things called eyelids.

00:14:06.160 --> 00:14:08.700
Now, eyelids might seem like
the most boring topic of all,

00:14:08.700 --> 00:14:10.500
but they are incredibly fascinating.

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:13.220
Today, we're going to talk
about how you can actually

00:14:13.220 --> 00:14:17.410
use your visual system to
increase your levels of alertness

00:14:17.410 --> 00:14:19.430
based on the neural circuits

00:14:19.430 --> 00:14:22.690
that link your brainstem
with your eyelids.

00:14:22.690 --> 00:14:24.840
And no, we are not going
to have a blinking contest,

00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:27.020
because I would win and you would lose,

00:14:27.020 --> 00:14:28.900
and that wouldn't be fun for you.

00:14:28.900 --> 00:14:33.900
So, let's talk about what
the eyes do for vision.

00:14:33.950 --> 00:14:36.300
Basically, the entire job of the eyes

00:14:36.300 --> 00:14:38.670
is to collect light information

00:14:38.670 --> 00:14:41.310
and send it off to the rest of the brain,

00:14:41.310 --> 00:14:43.170
in a form that the brain can understand.

00:14:43.170 --> 00:14:45.610
Remember, no light actually gets in

00:14:45.610 --> 00:14:47.050
past those neural retinas.

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:49.090
It gets to the neural retina,

00:14:49.090 --> 00:14:52.870
and we have specific cells in
the eye called photoreceptors.

00:14:52.870 --> 00:14:56.130
They come in two different
types, rods and cones.

00:14:56.130 --> 00:15:00.960
Cones are mainly responsible
for daytime vision,

00:15:00.960 --> 00:15:04.590
and the rods are mainly
responsible for vision at night

00:15:04.590 --> 00:15:07.223
or under low light conditions,
generally speaking.

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:12.270
So basically what happens
is if your eyelids are open,

00:15:12.270 --> 00:15:17.270
light comes into the eye,
the lens focuses that light,

00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:19.620
light is also just called
photons, light energy,

00:15:19.620 --> 00:15:20.713
onto the retina.

00:15:21.670 --> 00:15:24.820
These photoreceptors, the rods and cones,

00:15:24.820 --> 00:15:26.670
have chemical reactions inside them

00:15:26.670 --> 00:15:28.690
that involve things like vitamin A

00:15:29.850 --> 00:15:31.890
and that chemical reaction

00:15:31.890 --> 00:15:35.520
converts the light into electricity.

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:37.880
Now, that might seem incredibly abstract,

00:15:37.880 --> 00:15:40.290
but the way to think about
this is very similar to,

00:15:40.290 --> 00:15:42.650
for instance, you have
touch receptors on your skin

00:15:42.650 --> 00:15:44.620
and when you press on
those touch receptors,

00:15:44.620 --> 00:15:47.250
they convert pressure, physical pressure,

00:15:47.250 --> 00:15:49.260
into electrical information

00:15:49.260 --> 00:15:51.093
and those neurons send it up
to your spinal cord and brain,

00:15:51.093 --> 00:15:53.170
and you can register that somebody or you

00:15:53.170 --> 00:15:56.620
are touching the top of
your hand, as I'm doing now.

00:15:56.620 --> 00:15:57.613
With the eyes and the retina,

00:15:57.613 --> 00:15:59.320
it's just that light gets converted

00:15:59.320 --> 00:16:01.490
into electrical information.

00:16:01.490 --> 00:16:03.090
Within the eye, within the retina,

00:16:03.090 --> 00:16:06.853
there are then a series
of stages of processing,

00:16:07.690 --> 00:16:10.870
and that information eventually
gets sent into the brain

00:16:10.870 --> 00:16:13.440
by a very specific class of neurons.

00:16:13.440 --> 00:16:15.860
I would like you to know
the names of these neurons.

00:16:15.860 --> 00:16:17.730
They're called retinal ganglion cells.

00:16:17.730 --> 00:16:18.980
So the only thing you need to know

00:16:18.980 --> 00:16:21.270
about the neuroscience
of the eye at this point

00:16:21.270 --> 00:16:22.950
are that there are rods and cones.

00:16:22.950 --> 00:16:25.930
The cones are involved
in bright daytime vision

00:16:25.930 --> 00:16:28.993
and rods are involved in more
dusk or nighttime vision.

00:16:29.960 --> 00:16:32.710
And you've got these cells
called retinal ganglion cells

00:16:32.710 --> 00:16:35.750
that send the information
off to the rest of the brain.

00:16:35.750 --> 00:16:37.550
Now, here's what's incredible.

00:16:37.550 --> 00:16:39.040
I just want you to
ponder this for a second.

00:16:39.040 --> 00:16:40.493
This still blows my mind.

00:16:41.960 --> 00:16:43.923
Everything you see around you,

00:16:44.910 --> 00:16:47.670
you're not actually seeing
those objects directly.

00:16:47.670 --> 00:16:51.060
What you're doing is
you're making a best guess

00:16:51.060 --> 00:16:53.950
about what's there based on
the pattern of electricity

00:16:53.950 --> 00:16:55.940
that arrives in your brain.

00:16:55.940 --> 00:16:57.910
Now, that might just seem totally wild

00:16:57.910 --> 00:17:00.380
and hard to wrap your head around,

00:17:00.380 --> 00:17:02.240
but think about it this way,

00:17:02.240 --> 00:17:04.670
because this is the way it actually works.

00:17:04.670 --> 00:17:09.480
Let's take an example of a
color, like green or blue.

00:17:09.480 --> 00:17:12.470
You have cones in your eye

00:17:12.470 --> 00:17:16.460
that respond best to
the wavelength of light

00:17:16.460 --> 00:17:19.550
that is reflected off, say, a green apple.

00:17:19.550 --> 00:17:21.230
So, you don't actually
see the green apple.

00:17:21.230 --> 00:17:24.490
What you see is the light
bouncing off that green apple,

00:17:24.490 --> 00:17:27.170
and it goes into your eye,

00:17:27.170 --> 00:17:30.980
and you see it and perceive
it as round and green,

00:17:30.980 --> 00:17:33.680
but not because you see anything green.

00:17:33.680 --> 00:17:36.430
No green light arrives in your brain.

00:17:36.430 --> 00:17:39.610
What happens is your
brain actually compares

00:17:39.610 --> 00:17:43.620
the amount of green reflection
coming off that apple

00:17:43.620 --> 00:17:47.910
to the amount of red and blue around it.

00:17:47.910 --> 00:17:50.030
Well, you might say, well, the green apple

00:17:50.030 --> 00:17:53.110
is sitting on a brown
table or a white surface.

00:17:53.110 --> 00:17:56.080
Well, then, it will appear very green.

00:17:56.080 --> 00:17:58.850
Because the amount of wavelength of light

00:17:58.850 --> 00:18:01.500
for green is very high,

00:18:01.500 --> 00:18:04.020
and the amount for red is very low,

00:18:04.020 --> 00:18:06.760
and so, it looks very green, okay?

00:18:06.760 --> 00:18:10.000
So, we don't actually
see anything directly.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:13.330
What the brain is receiving
is a series of signals,

00:18:13.330 --> 00:18:16.990
electrical signals, and it's
comparing electrical signals,

00:18:16.990 --> 00:18:19.150
in order to come up with what
we call these perceptions.

00:18:19.150 --> 00:18:21.890
Like I see something green,
a green apple, or I see red.

00:18:21.890 --> 00:18:23.780
Let me give you a slightly
different example.

00:18:23.780 --> 00:18:26.660
If you were to play a key on the piano,

00:18:26.660 --> 00:18:28.540
let's say you play, I'm not a musician,

00:18:28.540 --> 00:18:31.910
but I'm going to, so hopefully
I won't get this too incorrectly

00:18:31.910 --> 00:18:34.300
but let's say you have like E sharp,

00:18:34.300 --> 00:18:36.540
and maybe it's like ding,
ding, ding, ding, ding.

00:18:36.540 --> 00:18:39.170
If the brain gets that signal,

00:18:39.170 --> 00:18:41.970
it doesn't actually know E that's what,

00:18:41.970 --> 00:18:43.660
it doesn't recognize it

00:18:43.660 --> 00:18:46.570
until you were to play
another key next to it,

00:18:46.570 --> 00:18:47.910
dun, dun, dun, dun,

00:18:47.910 --> 00:18:49.470
and what it does, it does the math,

00:18:49.470 --> 00:18:53.070
it does the subtraction,
and it compares those two.

00:18:53.070 --> 00:18:54.740
So when we see something green,

00:18:54.740 --> 00:18:57.280
or we see something red,
or we see something blue,

00:18:57.280 --> 00:18:58.750
we're not actually seeing it directly.

00:18:58.750 --> 00:19:00.500
The brain is making a guess about

00:19:00.500 --> 00:19:02.900
how green or red or blue that thing is

00:19:02.900 --> 00:19:07.070
by comparing what's around it, okay?

00:19:07.070 --> 00:19:08.820
And if that seems hard
to wrap your head around,

00:19:08.820 --> 00:19:11.460
don't worry, because we will explain it

00:19:11.460 --> 00:19:12.690
in more depth going forward.

00:19:12.690 --> 00:19:14.770
But I really want people
to understand this,

00:19:14.770 --> 00:19:19.770
that vision, eyesight, is not
looking at things directly,

00:19:20.170 --> 00:19:22.440
and that information getting
directly into your brain,

00:19:22.440 --> 00:19:24.160
it is translated.

00:19:24.160 --> 00:19:27.380
Light information is transformed
into electrical signals

00:19:27.380 --> 00:19:29.840
that your visual system
exquisitely understands.

00:19:29.840 --> 00:19:31.220
Now, what does this mean?

00:19:31.220 --> 00:19:32.560
Why should you care about this?

00:19:32.560 --> 00:19:36.290
Well, if you have a dog
like I do, or a cat,

00:19:36.290 --> 00:19:38.090
they are not colorblind,

00:19:38.090 --> 00:19:43.090
but they lack the cones
that respond to red,

00:19:43.200 --> 00:19:45.190
meaning long wavelength light.

00:19:45.190 --> 00:19:46.770
So what does that mean?

00:19:46.770 --> 00:19:48.900
That means that when they see green,

00:19:48.900 --> 00:19:50.933
it's different than the green you see.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:55.470
Not because that apple
is invisible to them,

00:19:55.470 --> 00:19:58.580
but because they aren't
able to compare it to red,

00:19:58.580 --> 00:20:00.350
and you are.

00:20:00.350 --> 00:20:03.220
As a consequence, when
they look at a green lawn,

00:20:03.220 --> 00:20:06.170
it looks more brownish or orange to them.

00:20:06.170 --> 00:20:10.640
When you wear a red shirt
in front of your dog or cat,

00:20:10.640 --> 00:20:13.280
if you see a stop sign
and they see a stop sign,

00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:16.610
they see orangish-brown, and you see red.

00:20:16.610 --> 00:20:18.430
presuming that you are a trichromat,

00:20:18.430 --> 00:20:20.730
meaning you have three-color vision.

00:20:20.730 --> 00:20:24.030
So, this is all to say that every animal

00:20:24.030 --> 00:20:25.700
sees the world differently,

00:20:25.700 --> 00:20:27.390
depending on whether or not they have

00:20:27.390 --> 00:20:29.560
one or two or three of
these different cones,

00:20:29.560 --> 00:20:31.680
the red, blue, or green cones.

00:20:31.680 --> 00:20:35.700
If you are a mantis shrimp of all things,

00:20:35.700 --> 00:20:38.070
you see hundreds of colors

00:20:38.920 --> 00:20:42.500
that human beings can't see, okay?

00:20:42.500 --> 00:20:46.020
Many things animals see into visual ranges

00:20:46.020 --> 00:20:47.610
that you and I can't see in.

00:20:47.610 --> 00:20:50.090
So for instance, a pit
viper senses heat emissions,

00:20:50.090 --> 00:20:53.210
it literally sees the
heat coming off of you

00:20:53.210 --> 00:20:55.780
or of an animal that they want to eat.

00:20:55.780 --> 00:20:57.780
If you are a ground squirrel,

00:20:57.780 --> 00:20:59.810
you can see ultraviolet light.

00:20:59.810 --> 00:21:00.870
This is going to sound kind of weird,

00:21:00.870 --> 00:21:03.760
but ground squirrels
actually signal one another

00:21:03.760 --> 00:21:06.790
by standing up outside
and shining sunlight

00:21:06.790 --> 00:21:08.930
off each other's stomachs to each other,

00:21:08.930 --> 00:21:10.790
signaling at a distance,
just like, you know,

00:21:10.790 --> 00:21:12.310
you could signal somebody with a mirror

00:21:12.310 --> 00:21:13.990
in sunlight at distance.

00:21:13.990 --> 00:21:15.290
There are species of primates,

00:21:15.290 --> 00:21:16.680
this isn't very pleasant to think about,

00:21:16.680 --> 00:21:18.190
that urinate on their hands,

00:21:18.190 --> 00:21:19.660
and then wipe it all over their stomach.

00:21:19.660 --> 00:21:21.310
and then use that sunlight

00:21:21.310 --> 00:21:23.290
to reflect different
signals to each other.

00:21:23.290 --> 00:21:24.130
I don't know what they're saying.

00:21:24.130 --> 00:21:25.720
We always assume it's
something cute and nice,

00:21:25.720 --> 00:21:27.630
but maybe they're insulting each other.

00:21:27.630 --> 00:21:29.630
So this actually gets right down

00:21:29.630 --> 00:21:31.280
to the heart of these bigger questions,

00:21:31.280 --> 00:21:33.110
like consciousness, what do we see?

00:21:33.110 --> 00:21:33.950
What's out there?

00:21:33.950 --> 00:21:38.220
How much of life is
really accessible to us?

00:21:38.220 --> 00:21:39.590
And I could go on and on, you know,

00:21:39.590 --> 00:21:42.200
this used to be kind
of an obsession of mine

00:21:42.200 --> 00:21:44.270
when I was coming up in the
field of visual neuroscience

00:21:44.270 --> 00:21:46.810
to understand how different
animals see the world

00:21:46.810 --> 00:21:48.360
compared to us.

00:21:48.360 --> 00:21:50.710
You know, I'll give one
more example, a diving bird,

00:21:50.710 --> 00:21:52.840
you know, a bird that
flies over the ocean.

00:21:52.840 --> 00:21:54.800
It has an incredible task.

00:21:54.800 --> 00:21:56.950
It has to both view the horizon,

00:21:56.950 --> 00:21:58.620
and it has to view schools of fish,

00:21:58.620 --> 00:21:59.940
and then, it has to make a trajectory

00:21:59.940 --> 00:22:03.560
down into the water and grab
one of those fish to eat.

00:22:03.560 --> 00:22:05.890
And the water has what's
called a refractory index.

00:22:05.890 --> 00:22:08.620
It actually shifts like a prism,

00:22:08.620 --> 00:22:10.330
the impression or the perception

00:22:10.330 --> 00:22:11.760
of where that fish is, right?

00:22:11.760 --> 00:22:15.140
If the bird sees the fish
right below it, it has to know,

00:22:15.140 --> 00:22:19.060
it has to adjust its diving
trajectory just right,

00:22:19.060 --> 00:22:20.510
because it knows that that fish

00:22:20.510 --> 00:22:22.540
actually isn't where it sees it.

00:22:22.540 --> 00:22:25.300
It's probably a few inches
ahead or to the side of that,

00:22:25.300 --> 00:22:29.200
because of the way that
water diverts the image.

00:22:29.200 --> 00:22:31.620
If you've ever dropped a
coin to the bottom of a pool,

00:22:31.620 --> 00:22:34.980
if you go straight down
looking at that location.

00:22:34.980 --> 00:22:36.410
If you were to look from
the top of the pool,

00:22:36.410 --> 00:22:38.170
and you dive straight down
with your eyes closed,

00:22:38.170 --> 00:22:41.150
you will miss, because the water refracts,

00:22:41.150 --> 00:22:43.370
it shifts the visual image.

00:22:43.370 --> 00:22:46.430
Well, diving birds have an arrangement

00:22:46.430 --> 00:22:49.610
of these retinal cells that
communicate to the brain

00:22:49.610 --> 00:22:51.790
that's both a streak to view the horizon,

00:22:51.790 --> 00:22:52.850
'cause they need to know where they are

00:22:52.850 --> 00:22:53.890
relative to the horizon,

00:22:53.890 --> 00:22:56.550
and they have a pupil like we
do on the bottom of their eye,

00:22:56.550 --> 00:23:00.060
so that they can make very
accurate dive and attacks

00:23:00.060 --> 00:23:01.160
on these schools of fish,

00:23:01.160 --> 00:23:03.470
and catch fish, and eat those fish.

00:23:03.470 --> 00:23:05.950
We just have pupils in
the middle of our eyes.

00:23:05.950 --> 00:23:08.167
So there's a ton about
the optics of the eye,

00:23:08.167 --> 00:23:10.530
and the way that it
communicates with the brain

00:23:10.530 --> 00:23:12.080
that allows us to see.

00:23:12.080 --> 00:23:13.540
We could spend hours talking about this,

00:23:13.540 --> 00:23:15.970
but what I'd like to embed in your mind

00:23:15.970 --> 00:23:19.320
is that what you experience
in the outside world

00:23:19.320 --> 00:23:23.330
is bottlenecked, it's
limited by which wavelengths,

00:23:23.330 --> 00:23:25.930
which colors if you will,
of light that you can see.

00:23:26.770 --> 00:23:27.910
That your brain is coming up

00:23:27.910 --> 00:23:29.850
with a best guess about what's there.

00:23:29.850 --> 00:23:32.860
It doesn't actually know what's there.

00:23:32.860 --> 00:23:36.110
And that your vision
is distinctly different

00:23:36.110 --> 00:23:38.140
from say, the vision of a dog

00:23:38.140 --> 00:23:40.190
or from the vision of
somebody who's a dichromat,

00:23:40.190 --> 00:23:42.560
meaning they don't have a red cone.

00:23:42.560 --> 00:23:46.920
A lot of people, in particular
about 1 in 80 males,

00:23:46.920 --> 00:23:49.150
lacks a red cone and
therefore, sees the world

00:23:49.150 --> 00:23:50.910
much the same way that Costello does.

00:23:50.910 --> 00:23:53.910
Although, he sees it from just
much lower toward the ground.

00:23:54.760 --> 00:23:57.180
So, that's what I'd like you to understand

00:23:57.180 --> 00:24:00.010
about the way the eye
communicates with the brain.

00:24:00.010 --> 00:24:02.280
I would also like you to understand

00:24:02.280 --> 00:24:06.890
that the brain itself
is making these guesses

00:24:06.890 --> 00:24:10.160
and that those guesses are largely right.

00:24:10.160 --> 00:24:11.720
How do I know that?

00:24:11.720 --> 00:24:13.260
Well, they're right
because when you reach out

00:24:13.260 --> 00:24:15.390
to grab a glass, most of
the time you grab the glass,

00:24:15.390 --> 00:24:17.370
and you don't miss, right?

00:24:17.370 --> 00:24:19.250
Most of the time, when you make judgments

00:24:19.250 --> 00:24:20.600
about the world around you,

00:24:20.600 --> 00:24:23.620
based on your visual impression of them,

00:24:23.620 --> 00:24:26.283
it allows you to move
functionally through the world.

00:24:27.270 --> 00:24:28.670
But let me give you some examples

00:24:28.670 --> 00:24:31.840
of where this guessing
is happening right now.

00:24:31.840 --> 00:24:34.780
And it's so incredible that, to this day,

00:24:34.780 --> 00:24:36.000
this still blows my mind.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:38.320
Cover one eye with one hand.

00:24:38.320 --> 00:24:40.570
If you're driving, maybe don't do this.

00:24:40.570 --> 00:24:42.340
If you're viewing the world around you,

00:24:42.340 --> 00:24:44.980
presumably you can see
everything that's out there.

00:24:44.980 --> 00:24:47.160
I could do this with one
eye or the other eye.

00:24:47.160 --> 00:24:48.810
You probably see better
out of one or the other,

00:24:48.810 --> 00:24:50.110
and we'll talk about that.

00:24:51.910 --> 00:24:53.870
You have a giant blind spot

00:24:53.870 --> 00:24:56.370
in the middle of your visual field.

00:24:56.370 --> 00:24:57.650
It's called your blind spot.

00:24:57.650 --> 00:25:00.260
It is the spot in which
the connections, the wires,

00:25:00.260 --> 00:25:01.900
from all those retinal ganglion cells

00:25:01.900 --> 00:25:04.650
exit the back of the eye and
head off toward the brain.

00:25:06.270 --> 00:25:09.010
In other words, you are
blind for a huge spot

00:25:09.010 --> 00:25:10.060
of your central vision.

00:25:10.060 --> 00:25:10.893
The part of your vision

00:25:10.893 --> 00:25:13.080
that's highest acuity, highest detail,

00:25:13.080 --> 00:25:15.610
and yet, you don't see that ever.

00:25:15.610 --> 00:25:17.910
You cover one eye, and
you see perfectly fine.

00:25:17.910 --> 00:25:19.150
And it's not just because your eye

00:25:19.150 --> 00:25:20.680
is moving around really quickly.

00:25:20.680 --> 00:25:23.940
Your brain is guessing
what's in that spot,

00:25:23.940 --> 00:25:25.540
which is absolutely incredible,

00:25:25.540 --> 00:25:28.160
and so, you don't see that blind spot.

00:25:28.160 --> 00:25:30.330
This is happening all the time.

00:25:30.330 --> 00:25:32.360
Now, when you have two eyes open,

00:25:32.360 --> 00:25:34.180
the way that your eyes are
positioned in your head

00:25:34.180 --> 00:25:35.490
and the way they view the world is such

00:25:35.490 --> 00:25:37.680
that they fill in each
other's blind spots,

00:25:37.680 --> 00:25:39.460
so it's pretty convenient.

00:25:39.460 --> 00:25:42.540
But if you cover one
eye, that's impossible,

00:25:42.540 --> 00:25:45.590
and yet, you still see
the world as complete.

00:25:45.590 --> 00:25:48.400
So the brain is doing
these incredible things.

00:25:48.400 --> 00:25:50.940
It's also creating
depth, a sense of depth.

00:25:50.940 --> 00:25:53.430
Even though what arrives from the retina

00:25:53.430 --> 00:25:56.550
is essentially a readout of a
two-dimensional, flat image,

00:25:56.550 --> 00:25:57.810
so it can sense depth.

00:25:57.810 --> 00:25:58.840
How do you know depth?

00:25:58.840 --> 00:26:01.140
Well, this is very simple.

00:26:01.140 --> 00:26:03.580
Things that are closer
to you tend to be larger

00:26:03.580 --> 00:26:05.320
than things that are far away.

00:26:05.320 --> 00:26:06.450
Things that are closer to you

00:26:06.450 --> 00:26:08.500
tend to look like they're moving faster.

00:26:08.500 --> 00:26:10.700
If you've ever been in a train
and you look to your side,

00:26:10.700 --> 00:26:14.140
the rungs on a fence, or the
train tracks going by you,

00:26:14.140 --> 00:26:15.310
look like they're going very fast.

00:26:15.310 --> 00:26:16.190
If you look off in the distance,

00:26:16.190 --> 00:26:18.230
they look like they're moving very slowly.

00:26:18.230 --> 00:26:21.200
And there are differences

00:26:21.200 --> 00:26:23.360
between what's close to you
and what's further away.

00:26:23.360 --> 00:26:24.920
So, a little house on the horizon,

00:26:24.920 --> 00:26:25.830
you don't look at it and say,

00:26:25.830 --> 00:26:27.740
oh, that must be a tiny, little house.

00:26:27.740 --> 00:26:29.270
You have some prior knowledge

00:26:29.270 --> 00:26:31.700
that things further away are smaller.

00:26:31.700 --> 00:26:33.150
So that's the main way that you do that.

00:26:33.150 --> 00:26:36.630
And you compare the location,

00:26:36.630 --> 00:26:40.440
at which information about
light lands on the two eyes.

00:26:40.440 --> 00:26:43.550
So your eyes are slightly
offset from one another.

00:26:43.550 --> 00:26:45.200
So that, for instance, if I look at you,

00:26:45.200 --> 00:26:46.527
if you were standing right
in front of me right now,

00:26:46.527 --> 00:26:48.040
and I were to look at you,

00:26:48.040 --> 00:26:49.680
the image of your face,

00:26:49.680 --> 00:26:52.480
the light bouncing off your
face to be more precise,

00:26:52.480 --> 00:26:55.600
lands on one eye in a
slightly different location

00:26:55.600 --> 00:26:59.910
than it does in the other eye,
and then the brain does math.

00:26:59.910 --> 00:27:01.480
It basically does the equivalent

00:27:01.480 --> 00:27:03.400
of geometry and trigonometry,

00:27:03.400 --> 00:27:08.270
and essentially figures out
how far away you are from me,

00:27:09.500 --> 00:27:10.540
which is just incredible.

00:27:10.540 --> 00:27:13.080
So the brain does all
this very, very fast,

00:27:13.080 --> 00:27:16.210
and the brain uses about 40 to 50%

00:27:16.210 --> 00:27:19.350
of its total real estate for vision.

00:27:19.350 --> 00:27:20.980
That's how important vision is.

00:27:20.980 --> 00:27:22.740
Now, for those of you that are blind,

00:27:22.740 --> 00:27:26.330
or low vision, or no vision,
that real estate in the brain

00:27:26.330 --> 00:27:31.200
will be taken over by neurons
that control sense of touch

00:27:31.200 --> 00:27:32.160
and a sense of hearing,

00:27:32.160 --> 00:27:34.840
and your, indeed, hearing
and touch are much better,

00:27:34.840 --> 00:27:39.400
higher acuity, and faster in blind people.

00:27:39.400 --> 00:27:42.450
But for most of you, who
I presume are sighted,

00:27:42.450 --> 00:27:44.180
this is how it works.

00:27:44.180 --> 00:27:48.290
So, that's kind of vision from
eye to brain in a nutshell.

00:27:48.290 --> 00:27:49.410
There are a bunch of different stations

00:27:49.410 --> 00:27:50.760
in the brain that do different things.

00:27:50.760 --> 00:27:52.510
That's eyesight.

00:27:52.510 --> 00:27:56.510
Now, I want to talk about
the other aspect of vision,

00:27:56.510 --> 00:27:58.780
which is the stuff that
you don't perceive,

00:27:58.780 --> 00:28:00.750
the subconscious stuff.

00:28:00.750 --> 00:28:02.780
And then, we'll transition directly

00:28:02.780 --> 00:28:05.440
into how you can use light and eyesight

00:28:05.440 --> 00:28:08.537
to control this other stuff
because it's very important

00:28:08.537 --> 00:28:13.537
and that other stuff is
mood, sleep, and appetite.

00:28:13.930 --> 00:28:17.320
And there are ways in which
you can use the same protocols

00:28:17.320 --> 00:28:18.800
that I will describe,

00:28:18.800 --> 00:28:22.560
in order to preserve and
even enhance your vision,

00:28:22.560 --> 00:28:26.470
your ability to see things
and consciously perceive them.

00:28:26.470 --> 00:28:28.050
So the protocols we will describe

00:28:28.050 --> 00:28:32.300
have a lot of carry over
to both conscious eyesight

00:28:32.300 --> 00:28:35.460
and to these subconscious
aspects of vision.

00:28:35.460 --> 00:28:37.390
And I just want you to
understand a little bit more

00:28:37.390 --> 00:28:40.460
about the science of seeing,
of eyesight and vision,

00:28:40.460 --> 00:28:43.570
and then all the protocols
will make perfect sense.

00:28:43.570 --> 00:28:45.740
So as amazing as eyesight is,

00:28:45.740 --> 00:28:48.710
it actually did not evolve for us

00:28:48.710 --> 00:28:51.930
to see shapes and colors
and motion and form.

00:28:51.930 --> 00:28:56.070
The most ancient cells in our eyes,

00:28:56.070 --> 00:29:00.700
and the reason we have eyes,
is to communicate information

00:29:00.700 --> 00:29:03.790
about time of day to the
rest of the brain and body.

00:29:03.790 --> 00:29:06.070
Remember, there's no
extraocular photo reception.

00:29:06.070 --> 00:29:07.870
There's no way for light information

00:29:07.870 --> 00:29:10.420
to get to all the cells of your body,

00:29:10.420 --> 00:29:12.430
but every cell in your body needs to know

00:29:12.430 --> 00:29:13.737
if it's night or day.

00:29:13.737 --> 00:29:15.360
And I talked a little bit about this

00:29:15.360 --> 00:29:17.970
on the, in the episodes on sleep,

00:29:17.970 --> 00:29:20.630
and this episode is not about sleep.

00:29:20.630 --> 00:29:24.490
But I want to emphasize that
there is a particular category

00:29:24.490 --> 00:29:25.700
of retinal ganglion cell,

00:29:25.700 --> 00:29:28.913
remember the neurons that
connect the retina to the brain,

00:29:30.110 --> 00:29:33.020
that is involved in a
special kind of vision

00:29:33.020 --> 00:29:35.040
that has nothing to do
with conscious perception

00:29:35.040 --> 00:29:36.270
of what's around you,

00:29:36.270 --> 00:29:39.600
and it's happening right now,
it's happening all the time.

00:29:39.600 --> 00:29:43.160
These are so-called melanopsin
retinal ganglion cells,

00:29:43.160 --> 00:29:46.250
named after the opsin that
they contain within them.

00:29:46.250 --> 00:29:48.150
They are essentially photoreceptors,

00:29:48.150 --> 00:29:49.810
remember before I said
there are photoreceptors

00:29:49.810 --> 00:29:50.770
and then these ganglion cells?

00:29:50.770 --> 00:29:54.050
Well, these melanopsin
cells, as the name suggests,

00:29:54.050 --> 00:29:58.093
melanopsin, have their own
photoreceptor built inside them.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:01.480
The opsin that they contain

00:30:01.480 --> 00:30:05.070
is actually very similar to the melanopsin

00:30:05.070 --> 00:30:09.980
that is present in the
skin of some amphibians

00:30:09.980 --> 00:30:14.450
and that causes those amphibians
to change their skin color

00:30:15.730 --> 00:30:17.770
in different light conditions.

00:30:17.770 --> 00:30:19.860
So you have, believe it or not,

00:30:19.860 --> 00:30:24.860
a little bit of frog skin
in your eye, so to speak.

00:30:25.680 --> 00:30:28.700
Okay, not exactly, but you
essentially have the equivalent

00:30:28.700 --> 00:30:31.793
of what frogs have on
their skin in your eye.

00:30:33.310 --> 00:30:36.023
If you are low vision or no vision,

00:30:37.250 --> 00:30:38.830
as long as you have retinas,

00:30:38.830 --> 00:30:41.070
it's very likely you
still have these cells,

00:30:41.070 --> 00:30:44.420
even though you can't see
or you don't see well.

00:30:44.420 --> 00:30:46.490
These cells, retinal ganglion cells,

00:30:46.490 --> 00:30:49.190
communicate to areas of the brain

00:30:49.190 --> 00:30:51.680
when particular qualities of light

00:30:51.680 --> 00:30:55.990
are present in your environment
and signal to the brain,

00:30:55.990 --> 00:31:00.523
therefore, that it's early
day or late in the day.

00:31:01.690 --> 00:31:03.130
These melanopsin ganglion cells

00:31:03.130 --> 00:31:05.880
are sometimes also called
intrinsically photosensitive cells

00:31:05.880 --> 00:31:08.540
because they behave like photoreceptors.

00:31:08.540 --> 00:31:10.130
What do these cells respond to,

00:31:10.130 --> 00:31:11.510
and why should you care about them?

00:31:11.510 --> 00:31:12.750
Well, you should care about them,

00:31:12.750 --> 00:31:14.730
because they regulate
when you'll get sleepy,

00:31:14.730 --> 00:31:18.640
when you'll feel awake, how
fast your metabolism is,

00:31:18.640 --> 00:31:20.490
excuse me, your blood sugar levels,

00:31:20.490 --> 00:31:24.513
your dopamine levels,
and your pain threshold.

00:31:25.510 --> 00:31:27.330
There are other factors
that impact those things,

00:31:27.330 --> 00:31:29.070
but they are one of the,

00:31:29.070 --> 00:31:31.450
if not the most powerful determinant,

00:31:31.450 --> 00:31:34.190
of those other things like
mood and pain threshold,

00:31:34.190 --> 00:31:36.483
sleepiness, wakefulness, et cetera.

00:31:37.600 --> 00:31:39.870
These melanopsin ganglion cells

00:31:39.870 --> 00:31:44.870
have been shown by the
Nitz Group, N-I-T-Z,

00:31:46.020 --> 00:31:47.380
up at University of Washington,

00:31:47.380 --> 00:31:49.780
and by Samer Hattar's lab
and David Burson's lab,

00:31:49.780 --> 00:31:51.420
and a number of other people's labs,

00:31:51.420 --> 00:31:54.410
Satchin Panda, Prevencio, et cetera,

00:31:54.410 --> 00:31:56.660
a number of excellent labs in neuroscience

00:31:58.200 --> 00:32:00.060
to set the circadian clock

00:32:00.060 --> 00:32:03.630
and to respond best to the contrast

00:32:03.630 --> 00:32:05.850
between blue and yellow light

00:32:05.850 --> 00:32:10.850
of the sort that lands on the
cells when you view the sun,

00:32:12.190 --> 00:32:14.090
when it's a so-called low solar angle,

00:32:14.090 --> 00:32:15.330
when it's low in the sky,

00:32:15.330 --> 00:32:18.210
either in the morning or in the evening,

00:32:18.210 --> 00:32:19.380
what does all this mean?

00:32:19.380 --> 00:32:21.550
It means, and here's the first protocol,

00:32:21.550 --> 00:32:23.940
and you've probably
heard me say this before,

00:32:23.940 --> 00:32:26.490
but is appropriate to this
episode to say it again.

00:32:27.840 --> 00:32:32.330
If you are not viewing the sun, sunlight,

00:32:32.330 --> 00:32:34.030
even through cloud cover,

00:32:34.030 --> 00:32:37.400
for two to 10 minutes in
the early part of the day,

00:32:37.400 --> 00:32:39.640
when the sun is still low in the sky

00:32:39.640 --> 00:32:42.240
and doing the same thing
again in the evening,

00:32:42.240 --> 00:32:45.870
you are severely disrupting
your sleep rhythms,

00:32:45.870 --> 00:32:49.180
your mood, your hormones, your metabolism,

00:32:49.180 --> 00:32:51.630
your pain threshold,
and many other factors,

00:32:51.630 --> 00:32:54.800
including your ability to
learn and remember information.

00:32:54.800 --> 00:32:58.510
The most central and important
aspect of our biology,

00:32:58.510 --> 00:33:00.470
and perhaps our psychology as well,

00:33:00.470 --> 00:33:05.470
is to anchor ourselves in
time, to know when we exist.

00:33:07.110 --> 00:33:10.750
Okay, it sounds a little bit
abstract and philosophical,

00:33:10.750 --> 00:33:11.583
but it's not.

00:33:11.583 --> 00:33:15.550
And we don't know time as a real thing

00:33:15.550 --> 00:33:16.770
because of watches and clocks.

00:33:16.770 --> 00:33:19.400
We know time at a biological level,

00:33:19.400 --> 00:33:22.350
based on where the sun is and where,

00:33:22.350 --> 00:33:25.270
which of course is where
we are relative to the sun,

00:33:25.270 --> 00:33:26.840
because the earth is spinning around.

00:33:26.840 --> 00:33:29.330
Now, what does this mean for a protocol?

00:33:29.330 --> 00:33:33.660
It means, see, get that light
in your eyes early in the day,

00:33:33.660 --> 00:33:35.190
and anytime you want to be awake.

00:33:35.190 --> 00:33:36.470
So try and get as much sunlight

00:33:36.470 --> 00:33:38.200
in your eyes during the
day as you safely can.

00:33:38.200 --> 00:33:41.300
We'll talk about eye safety
this episode in depth.

00:33:41.300 --> 00:33:45.850
And the blue light and the
contrast of that blue yellow,

00:33:45.850 --> 00:33:48.950
remember we don't see blue,
this is all subconscious.

00:33:48.950 --> 00:33:51.130
This is blue reflections
coming off of sunlight.

00:33:51.130 --> 00:33:53.170
Blue light, we've been
told is so terrible for us,

00:33:53.170 --> 00:33:54.840
it is absolutely essential and wonderful

00:33:54.840 --> 00:33:56.330
for waking up the brain,

00:33:56.330 --> 00:33:59.340
for triggering all sorts of
positive biological reactions,

00:33:59.340 --> 00:34:01.650
but it needs to be
viewed early in the day.

00:34:01.650 --> 00:34:02.840
If you can't see sunlight,

00:34:02.840 --> 00:34:06.400
because it's the thick
cloud cover of say a,

00:34:06.400 --> 00:34:08.430
you know, you're in
the UK and it's winter,

00:34:08.430 --> 00:34:11.640
then artificial lights,
especially blue lights,

00:34:11.640 --> 00:34:13.698
would be very beneficial to you.

00:34:13.698 --> 00:34:16.940
We need a lot of this light
and its contrast with yellow,

00:34:16.940 --> 00:34:19.200
in order to trigger
these melanopsin cells,

00:34:19.200 --> 00:34:21.600
which will then trigger
your circadian clock,

00:34:21.600 --> 00:34:22.740
which sits above the roof of your mouth,

00:34:22.740 --> 00:34:24.810
which will signal every cell in your body,

00:34:24.810 --> 00:34:27.100
including temperature, rhythms, et cetera.

00:34:27.100 --> 00:34:29.560
So first things first, your visual system

