positioning your computer
screen up at eye level,

00:57:42.920 --> 00:57:46.410
or sometimes having it
actually above eye level,

00:57:46.410 --> 00:57:49.150
can actually create
wakefulness and alertness

00:57:49.150 --> 00:57:50.440
for the work that you're going to do.

00:57:50.440 --> 00:57:53.270
This is simply because of this connection

00:57:53.270 --> 00:57:55.010
between the brainstem circuits

00:57:55.010 --> 00:57:58.380
and the other neural circuits
that control wakefulness

00:57:58.380 --> 00:58:01.970
and eyelids opening and looking up.

00:58:01.970 --> 00:58:04.520
Okay, so it, again,
it's remarkably simple,

00:58:04.520 --> 00:58:06.610
almost laughably simple, but it's grounded

00:58:06.610 --> 00:58:08.630
in some of the most hardwired,

00:58:08.630 --> 00:58:09.830
meaning present from birth,

00:58:09.830 --> 00:58:12.200
aspects of our neural circuitry.

00:58:12.200 --> 00:58:15.520
And norepinephrine released
from locus coeruleus

00:58:15.520 --> 00:58:16.990
isn't just a mouthful,

00:58:16.990 --> 00:58:21.020
it's a really interesting
and powerful mechanism

00:58:21.020 --> 00:58:22.650
for how the rest of the brain wakes up.

00:58:22.650 --> 00:58:25.290
Locus coeruleus hoses
the rest of your brain

00:58:25.290 --> 00:58:29.020
with norepinephrine, in order
to wake up those circuits

00:58:29.020 --> 00:58:30.240
for work and attention.

00:58:30.240 --> 00:58:34.230
And so, eyes up is actually a way,

00:58:34.230 --> 00:58:36.590
a route into increased alertness.

00:58:36.590 --> 00:58:39.530
Eyes down is a route into sleepiness,

00:58:39.530 --> 00:58:41.550
into reduced alertness.

00:58:41.550 --> 00:58:45.373
And I have only one
friend that texts up here,

00:58:45.373 --> 00:58:47.520
like on the street
holds his phone up here.

00:58:47.520 --> 00:58:49.040
It looks ridiculous.

00:58:49.040 --> 00:58:52.340
And yet, you know, if we were trying

00:58:52.340 --> 00:58:54.140
to create more sense of alertness,

00:58:54.140 --> 00:58:55.340
if that's your goal,

00:58:55.340 --> 00:58:58.560
positioning computer
screens up high, chin up,

00:58:58.560 --> 00:59:01.330
looking up if you need to kind
of create an alertness signal,

00:59:01.330 --> 00:59:03.640
not always being chin down and texting,

00:59:03.640 --> 00:59:06.800
or working into typewriters,
or reading below us.

00:59:06.800 --> 00:59:10.470
is actually going to send a
recurring wakefulness signal.

00:59:10.470 --> 00:59:11.870
When things are up, we tend to be alert.

00:59:11.870 --> 00:59:14.190
When everything's focused
down, including our eyes,

00:59:14.190 --> 00:59:15.720
it tends to have a more suppressive

00:59:15.720 --> 00:59:17.490
or sedative type signaling

00:59:17.490 --> 00:59:19.180
to the deeper centers of the brain.

00:59:19.180 --> 00:59:22.170
Now, before we move on to
the science, and tools,

00:59:22.170 --> 00:59:24.690
and protocols related to pattern vision,

00:59:24.690 --> 00:59:26.850
I want to mention another
study that was done

00:59:26.850 --> 00:59:28.460
by the University of Pennsylvania.

00:59:28.460 --> 00:59:31.730
They have a terrific group
there that works on sleep.

00:59:31.730 --> 00:59:33.410
They made an important discovery

00:59:33.410 --> 00:59:35.810
that I think everybody should know about,

00:59:35.810 --> 00:59:39.950
which is that children that sleep in rooms

00:59:39.950 --> 00:59:44.900
that have a nightlight or dim
lights are much more likely

00:59:44.900 --> 00:59:47.563
to develop myopia, nearsightedness.

00:59:48.840 --> 00:59:53.130
Conversely, children that
sleep in very dark rooms,

00:59:53.130 --> 00:59:57.653
so either very dim
nightlights or complete black,

00:59:58.530 --> 01:00:01.460
they have a much lower,
statistically speaking,

01:00:01.460 --> 01:00:03.170
a significantly lower probability

01:00:03.170 --> 01:00:06.160
of developing myopia, nearsightedness.

01:00:06.160 --> 01:00:08.000
Now, why is that?

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:12.440
It's because the wavelengths
of light that matter

01:00:12.440 --> 01:00:14.233
for these melanopsin cells,

01:00:15.160 --> 01:00:17.623
oftentimes can get through the eyelids.

01:00:18.660 --> 01:00:21.880
And that's particularly true for children

01:00:21.880 --> 01:00:23.810
and people that have thin eyelids.

01:00:23.810 --> 01:00:26.400
Some people, like me,
have very thin eyelids.

01:00:26.400 --> 01:00:27.983
I've been told this before.

01:00:28.830 --> 01:00:30.180
Not many people touch my eyelids,

01:00:30.180 --> 01:00:33.570
but among those that have,
I have very thin eyelids.

01:00:33.570 --> 01:00:36.830
I notice I have very thin eyelids
compared to say, Costello.

01:00:36.830 --> 01:00:38.240
Now, Costello's eyes droop.

01:00:38.240 --> 01:00:40.660
He can't even close his eyes
all the way they're so droopy.

01:00:40.660 --> 01:00:43.640
But many people have thin eyelids,

01:00:43.640 --> 01:00:45.700
and those people are going
to be even more prone

01:00:45.700 --> 01:00:48.280
to light coming in through the eyelid.

01:00:48.280 --> 01:00:52.580
So for parents, for kids, and for adults,

01:00:52.580 --> 01:00:54.980
you really want to try to get to a place

01:00:54.980 --> 01:00:57.410
where you can sleep in a completely black

01:00:57.410 --> 01:00:58.960
or dark environment.

01:00:58.960 --> 01:01:00.930
One little exposure to light, no big deal.

01:01:00.930 --> 01:01:03.650
But this ties back to the other protocol

01:01:03.650 --> 01:01:06.460
that I've described before in
the mood and sleep episodes,

01:01:06.460 --> 01:01:08.630
which is that viewing light,

01:01:08.630 --> 01:01:10.290
even a very low intensity

01:01:10.290 --> 01:01:12.450
between the hours of 10:00 PM and 4:00 AM

01:01:12.450 --> 01:01:14.490
is extremely detrimental to the dopamine

01:01:14.490 --> 01:01:17.150
and other mood producing
systems of the brain.

01:01:17.150 --> 01:01:19.760
It can negatively impact
learning, and immunity,

01:01:19.760 --> 01:01:21.220
and even blood sugar,

01:01:21.220 --> 01:01:23.400
and make people type two diabetes prone

01:01:23.400 --> 01:01:26.160
by way of communication
from these melanopsin cells

01:01:26.160 --> 01:01:28.700
to a structure in the
brain called the habenula.

01:01:28.700 --> 01:01:30.540
Why am I throwing out all this verbiage?

01:01:30.540 --> 01:01:32.450
Well, because people have
asked for more mechanisms.

01:01:32.450 --> 01:01:33.470
So, if you really want to know,

01:01:33.470 --> 01:01:35.250
when you look at blue light

01:01:35.250 --> 01:01:37.010
or if blue light is getting
in through your eyelids

01:01:37.010 --> 01:01:38.340
in the middle of the night,

01:01:38.340 --> 01:01:39.970
it is likely distorting

01:01:39.970 --> 01:01:43.630
this lens accommodation
mechanism in the eye

01:01:43.630 --> 01:01:47.260
and leading to myopia in some cases.

01:01:47.260 --> 01:01:49.427
So, that's one reason to
avoid blue light exposure

01:01:49.427 --> 01:01:51.440
and bright light exposure,
even nightlight exposure,

01:01:51.440 --> 01:01:52.750
in middle of the night.

01:01:52.750 --> 01:01:55.340
Viewing any light of bright intensity

01:01:55.340 --> 01:01:58.030
between the hours of 10:00 PM and 4:00 AM

01:01:58.030 --> 01:02:01.040
on a consistent basis is
going to suppress dopamine,

01:02:01.040 --> 01:02:02.680
because of the way that that light

01:02:02.680 --> 01:02:04.170
activates these melanopsin cells,

01:02:04.170 --> 01:02:06.770
and the habenula, and the dopamine system.

01:02:06.770 --> 01:02:08.680
So it's all very simple,

01:02:08.680 --> 01:02:12.290
get as much bright light
as you can safely, right?

01:02:12.290 --> 01:02:13.800
You never want to look
at any light so bright

01:02:13.800 --> 01:02:16.760
that it's painful look
at, during the daytime.

01:02:16.760 --> 01:02:18.960
Try and go without sunglasses,
unless you need them.

01:02:18.960 --> 01:02:21.110
Now, I wear sunglasses for sake of sport

01:02:21.110 --> 01:02:23.180
and sake when it's really bright out,

01:02:23.180 --> 01:02:25.040
but I try to get two hours a day

01:02:25.040 --> 01:02:27.370
of working outside or being outside,

01:02:27.370 --> 01:02:30.730
even if there's cloud cover,
that's going to offset myopia.

01:02:30.730 --> 01:02:32.330
It's going to help you get better sleep.

01:02:32.330 --> 01:02:35.310
It's going to support mood
and metabolism, et cetera.

01:02:35.310 --> 01:02:37.500
And at night, if you're sleeping

01:02:37.500 --> 01:02:38.560
with a lot of lights in the room,

01:02:38.560 --> 01:02:41.450
and especially, if there are
kids that need a nightlight,

01:02:41.450 --> 01:02:43.900
you should try and wean
them off that nightlight,

01:02:43.900 --> 01:02:45.240
because it's going to be beneficial

01:02:45.240 --> 01:02:47.310
for their vision to wean
them off that nightlight

01:02:47.310 --> 01:02:49.270
and put them into a darker environment.

01:02:49.270 --> 01:02:50.880
Obviously, you want to get
them emotionally comfortable

01:02:50.880 --> 01:02:52.480
with that first.

01:02:52.480 --> 01:02:56.020
Now, let's talk about pattern
vision, actual seeing things,

01:02:56.020 --> 01:02:58.040
like faces and colors, et cetera.

01:02:58.040 --> 01:03:01.280
I'm presuming that some of
you out there are colorblind.

01:03:01.280 --> 01:03:05.290
We can all help the red-green
colorblind folks out there

01:03:05.290 --> 01:03:08.690
by not using red in slides and diagrams,

01:03:08.690 --> 01:03:10.230
and on menus, and things of that sort.

01:03:10.230 --> 01:03:12.030
Try and use magenta instead.

01:03:12.030 --> 01:03:15.560
They can see the contrast
between magenta and green

01:03:15.560 --> 01:03:19.010
better than if there's red and green.

01:03:19.010 --> 01:03:21.160
So, be kind to the
colorblind folks out there.

01:03:21.160 --> 01:03:23.080
It's actually a fair percentage.

01:03:23.080 --> 01:03:24.960
And there are a lot of
different kinds of colorblind.

01:03:24.960 --> 01:03:28.310
I should just mention some
people are true monochromats.

01:03:28.310 --> 01:03:29.700
They see the world in black and white.

01:03:29.700 --> 01:03:31.263
That's exceedingly rare.

01:03:32.120 --> 01:03:35.150
Most colorblind people,
colorblind in quotes,

01:03:35.150 --> 01:03:36.900
are red-green colorblind,

01:03:36.900 --> 01:03:39.680
meaning they lack red cone photo pigment,

01:03:39.680 --> 01:03:42.130
meaning they can't see
long wavelengths of light.

01:03:42.130 --> 01:03:45.550
So they see the world much
as a canine or a cat does,

01:03:45.550 --> 01:03:48.270
where they don't get
the green-red contrast.

01:03:48.270 --> 01:03:50.540
That's why we call it
red-green colorblind.

01:03:50.540 --> 01:03:52.000
They have the green cones,

01:03:52.000 --> 01:03:54.030
but they can't do the contrast comparison

01:03:54.030 --> 01:03:56.720
that I described at the
beginning of the episode.

01:03:56.720 --> 01:04:00.450
So use magenta, and they
will be able to see things.

01:04:00.450 --> 01:04:02.440
You wonder why stop signs and stop lights

01:04:02.440 --> 01:04:03.940
and things aren't in magenta.

01:04:03.940 --> 01:04:05.410
Well, because the world is unkind

01:04:05.410 --> 01:04:07.800
to the red-green color blind individuals,

01:04:07.800 --> 01:04:09.860
and they have to learn the
position of those lights

01:04:09.860 --> 01:04:11.400
in the street lights.

01:04:11.400 --> 01:04:13.440
And they have to learn
the shapes of signs,

01:04:13.440 --> 01:04:14.360
which they can do readily,

01:04:14.360 --> 01:04:16.740
and it usually says stop on it as well.

01:04:16.740 --> 01:04:19.660
But if you care about
colorblind folks, which I do,

01:04:19.660 --> 01:04:21.290
then we could all do them a service

01:04:21.290 --> 01:04:24.620
by, I think by law actually in the U.S.,

01:04:24.620 --> 01:04:27.363
menus are required to be
colorblind accessible.

01:04:28.890 --> 01:04:31.500
How can you improve your vision?

01:04:31.500 --> 01:04:34.010
How can you get better at seeing things?

01:04:34.010 --> 01:04:35.980
Well, one way is to make sure

01:04:35.980 --> 01:04:39.390
that you spend at least
10 minutes a day total,

01:04:39.390 --> 01:04:42.330
at least, viewing things
off in the distance.

01:04:42.330 --> 01:04:45.420
So that would be well
over half a mile or more,

01:04:45.420 --> 01:04:46.760
try and see a horizon,

01:04:46.760 --> 01:04:50.110
try and get your vision out to a location

01:04:50.110 --> 01:04:53.103
that's beyond the four walls
of your house or apartment,

01:04:53.990 --> 01:04:56.700
or the doors of your car, and
the windshield of your car.

01:04:56.700 --> 01:04:59.390
I know that can be hard to
do, but it's very valuable.

01:04:59.390 --> 01:05:00.980
If you live in a city like New York

01:05:00.980 --> 01:05:02.860
and it's skyscrapers everywhere,

01:05:02.860 --> 01:05:04.130
you've probably experienced

01:05:04.130 --> 01:05:06.380
the incredible sense of relaxation,

01:05:06.380 --> 01:05:08.110
and it's aesthetically beautiful,

01:05:08.110 --> 01:05:10.270
when you are walking down
one of these long avenues,

01:05:10.270 --> 01:05:12.150
and you turn, and I think they have

01:05:12.150 --> 01:05:14.100
a name for this in New York,

01:05:14.100 --> 01:05:17.580
where the sunset is suddenly visible

01:05:17.580 --> 01:05:20.330
along a long avenue
between some skyscrapers.

01:05:20.330 --> 01:05:22.320
And it's just very relaxing to be able,

01:05:22.320 --> 01:05:23.750
suddenly, to see at a distance,

01:05:23.750 --> 01:05:25.870
and that's actually
because this eye mechanism

01:05:25.870 --> 01:05:28.180
of relaxing the lens

01:05:29.200 --> 01:05:32.310
and relaxing some of the
musculature around the eyes

01:05:32.310 --> 01:05:34.060
sends signals deep into the brainstem

01:05:34.060 --> 01:05:35.450
that release some of the centers

01:05:35.450 --> 01:05:39.100
that are involved in
alertness, AKA stress.

01:05:39.100 --> 01:05:40.920
And it's very pleasant for a reason.

01:05:40.920 --> 01:05:45.290
It's not a, it's not a
placebo effect if you will.

01:05:45.290 --> 01:05:46.570
There are a bunch of neurochemicals

01:05:46.570 --> 01:05:48.340
and things that are associated with that.

01:05:48.340 --> 01:05:49.860
So try and see at a distance,

01:05:49.860 --> 01:05:51.420
because it's good for your eyesight.

01:05:51.420 --> 01:05:54.060
It'll keep this lens nice and elastic,

01:05:54.060 --> 01:05:56.690
and the muscles nice and
strong that move the lens,

01:05:56.690 --> 01:06:00.510
and it has this relaxing component to it.

01:06:00.510 --> 01:06:05.090
Now, our visual system is
exquisitely tuned to motion,

01:06:05.090 --> 01:06:07.130
not just our self-generated motion,

01:06:07.130 --> 01:06:08.920
but the motion of things around us.

01:06:08.920 --> 01:06:11.050
And one of the things that it does

01:06:11.050 --> 01:06:13.780
is something called smooth pursuit.

01:06:13.780 --> 01:06:18.780
Smooth pursuit is our ability
to track individual objects

01:06:18.960 --> 01:06:21.560
moving, as the name suggests,
smoothly through space

01:06:22.510 --> 01:06:23.983
in various trajectories.

01:06:24.840 --> 01:06:29.840
You can actually train
or improve your vision

01:06:29.980 --> 01:06:32.747
by looking at smooth pursuit stimuli,

01:06:32.747 --> 01:06:34.030
and that sounds really boring.

01:06:34.030 --> 01:06:36.060
What you can do is, and
I'll provide a link to some

01:06:36.060 --> 01:06:37.110
that I think are pretty good

01:06:37.110 --> 01:06:39.440
that are used in various clinics,

01:06:39.440 --> 01:06:42.400
ophthalmology and optometry clinics.

01:06:42.400 --> 01:06:45.040
You can actually take
a few minutes each day,

01:06:45.040 --> 01:06:46.700
or maybe if you don't do it each day,

01:06:46.700 --> 01:06:47.930
you could every third day or so,

01:06:47.930 --> 01:06:50.490
and actually just visually track a ball.

01:06:50.490 --> 01:06:52.630
Sometimes it's moving in and
kind of an infinity symbol.

01:06:52.630 --> 01:06:55.070
Sometimes it's more of a sawtooth.

01:06:55.070 --> 01:06:56.720
Sometimes it's changing speed.

01:06:56.720 --> 01:06:59.820
Sometimes the cue that you're following,

01:06:59.820 --> 01:07:03.380
the little target, is
dilating and contracting.

01:07:03.380 --> 01:07:06.560
This is going to keep the
muscles, I want to be clear,

01:07:06.560 --> 01:07:09.440
this is going to keep
the extraocular muscles

01:07:09.440 --> 01:07:11.240
conditioned and strong

01:07:11.240 --> 01:07:15.500
and allow you to have a
healthy smooth pursuit system.

01:07:15.500 --> 01:07:17.540
Remember, the brain follows the eye.

01:07:17.540 --> 01:07:19.710
It follows the movements of the eye.

01:07:19.710 --> 01:07:20.900
It has to deal with that.

01:07:20.900 --> 01:07:22.620
And the neural circuits within the brain

01:07:22.620 --> 01:07:25.600
have to cope with changes
in smooth pursuit.

01:07:25.600 --> 01:07:27.580
So if you're doing a
lot of reading up close,

01:07:27.580 --> 01:07:28.720
you're not viewing horizons,

01:07:28.720 --> 01:07:31.780
you're not getting a lot of
smooth pursuit type stimulation

01:07:31.780 --> 01:07:35.190
from your life, or you're just getting it

01:07:35.190 --> 01:07:37.360
within the confines of a
little box on your phone,

01:07:37.360 --> 01:07:40.590
like your smooth pursuit is
over, you know, millimeters

01:07:40.590 --> 01:07:43.110
or what we always talk
in terms of visual angle,

01:07:43.110 --> 01:07:44.920
but the amount of degrees of visual angle.

01:07:44.920 --> 01:07:46.370
But if you're just
looking at smooth pursuit

01:07:46.370 --> 01:07:48.070
in this little tiny box on your phone,

01:07:48.070 --> 01:07:49.400
or on your computer screen,

01:07:49.400 --> 01:07:51.470
and you're not looking at
objects in your environment

01:07:51.470 --> 01:07:52.970
like swooping birds and things like that,

01:07:52.970 --> 01:07:53.960
which I'm guessing many of you

01:07:53.960 --> 01:07:55.600
are not spending your time doing,

01:07:55.600 --> 01:07:57.400
well, these mechanisms for smooth pursuit

01:07:57.400 --> 01:07:58.460
will get worse over time.

01:07:58.460 --> 01:07:59.610
Your vision will get worse.

01:07:59.610 --> 01:08:01.610
And so, while I prefer that people

01:08:01.610 --> 01:08:03.110
get out into the real world

01:08:03.110 --> 01:08:07.080
and experience smooth pursuit
tracking of visual objects,

01:08:07.080 --> 01:08:07.913
I don't know, maybe it's a good reason

01:08:07.913 --> 01:08:09.473
to go to a hockey game or, you know,

01:08:09.473 --> 01:08:11.130
and try and keep your eye on the puck,

01:08:11.130 --> 01:08:12.180
which I can never seem to do.

01:08:12.180 --> 01:08:13.920
It moves so fast.

01:08:13.920 --> 01:08:16.570
Or I guess this is a good
reason to watch live sports

01:08:16.570 --> 01:08:18.830
if that's your thing, or
to watch a tennis match,

01:08:18.830 --> 01:08:19.930
like a cat, like a kitten,

01:08:19.930 --> 01:08:21.970
watching the ball go back and forth,

01:08:21.970 --> 01:08:25.080
whatever, watching kids play,
it doesn't really matter.

01:08:25.080 --> 01:08:29.990
The idea is that you want to
use the visual system regularly

01:08:29.990 --> 01:08:31.030
for what it was designed for,

01:08:31.030 --> 01:08:33.480
and smooth pursuit is a great way

01:08:33.480 --> 01:08:36.460
to keep the visual and
motion tracking systems

01:08:36.460 --> 01:08:38.840
of the brain and the eye
and the extraocular muscles

01:08:38.840 --> 01:08:41.150
working in a really
nice coordinate fashion.

01:08:41.150 --> 01:08:44.780
I would say five to 10 minutes,

01:08:44.780 --> 01:08:46.940
three times a week will be great.

01:08:46.940 --> 01:08:47.970
If you care about your vision,

01:08:47.970 --> 01:08:50.210
you can train your vision in this way.

01:08:50.210 --> 01:08:53.580
The other one is to train accommodation.

01:08:53.580 --> 01:08:55.880
There are a lot of videos out
there, I want to be clear,

01:08:55.880 --> 01:09:00.030
on the internet, some of
which are from clinicians,

01:09:00.030 --> 01:09:01.360
some of which are not.

01:09:01.360 --> 01:09:02.640
Some of which are from scientists,

01:09:02.640 --> 01:09:04.610
some of which are from other sources,

01:09:04.610 --> 01:09:07.040
talking about things you can do

01:09:07.040 --> 01:09:09.610
to make your vision better,
to improve your vision.

01:09:09.610 --> 01:09:11.810
Most of those are geared

01:09:11.810 --> 01:09:14.317
toward improving the
extraocular eye muscles,

01:09:14.317 --> 01:09:18.160
but I did consult with
our chair of ophthalmology

01:09:18.160 --> 01:09:21.020
at Stanford School of
Medicine, Jeff Goldberg,

01:09:21.020 --> 01:09:23.810
who's an MD and a PhD,
a phenomenal scientist,

01:09:23.810 --> 01:09:25.640
and a phenomenal clinician,

01:09:25.640 --> 01:09:28.400
and incidentally, a
phenomenal chairman as well,

01:09:28.400 --> 01:09:31.700
about what sorts of things, tools,

01:09:31.700 --> 01:09:35.230
are actually beneficial for
pattern vision and sight,

01:09:35.230 --> 01:09:37.640
because there's just so much
out there on the internet.

01:09:37.640 --> 01:09:40.990
Not all of which is
accurate or good, frankly.

01:09:40.990 --> 01:09:43.970
And he agreed that a
smooth pursuit stimulus,

01:09:43.970 --> 01:09:47.950
that kind of training,
as well as, or exercise,

01:09:47.950 --> 01:09:49.750
as well as near far.

01:09:49.750 --> 01:09:52.210
So spending a few minutes,
you might even just do this

01:09:52.210 --> 01:09:54.960
for two minutes of looking
at something up close,

01:09:54.960 --> 01:09:57.200
that's going to activate these
accommodation mechanisms,

01:09:57.200 --> 01:09:59.270
and then moving it at arms length,

01:09:59.270 --> 01:10:01.400
and focusing on it for five, 10 seconds,

01:10:01.400 --> 01:10:03.870
maybe more, maybe 15 or 20 seconds,

01:10:03.870 --> 01:10:07.510
then slowly moving it into
a location, and then out.

01:10:07.510 --> 01:10:09.740
This is actually a lot
like the visual training

01:10:09.740 --> 01:10:13.770
that's done post-concussion
to try and repair,

01:10:13.770 --> 01:10:16.350
actually repair some of
the balance, and motor,

01:10:16.350 --> 01:10:20.380
and visual, and cognitive
aspects of the brain.

01:10:20.380 --> 01:10:21.850
And we are going to have a guest on

01:10:21.850 --> 01:10:23.570
at a future time that,

01:10:23.570 --> 01:10:26.610
to deal with concussion and
some post-concussion training.

01:10:26.610 --> 01:10:28.750
A lot of post concussion
recovery and training

01:10:28.750 --> 01:10:30.420
centers around the visual system.

01:10:30.420 --> 01:10:33.840
Not just because people are
trying to recover their vision

01:10:33.840 --> 01:10:35.580
and their sense of balance,

01:10:35.580 --> 01:10:37.340
but because, as I mentioned earlier,

01:10:37.340 --> 01:10:40.520
the brain's ability to make
sense of its environment,

01:10:40.520 --> 01:10:42.880
and the brain's ability to parse time,

01:10:42.880 --> 01:10:44.840
not just on the day-night schedule,

01:10:44.840 --> 01:10:49.230
but also shorter time intervals,
follows the visual system.

01:10:49.230 --> 01:10:51.170
Something we'll turn to a
little bit more at the end.

01:10:51.170 --> 01:10:52.100
So what does this mean?

01:10:52.100 --> 01:10:55.750
The tool is, spend two to three minutes

01:10:55.750 --> 01:10:56.870
doing smooth pursuit.

01:10:56.870 --> 01:10:59.076
There's some programs on YouTube,

01:10:59.076 --> 01:11:00.890
or you can just look up
smooth pursuit stimulus,

01:11:00.890 --> 01:11:04.270
and I'll provide a link to
a couple I like as well.

01:11:04.270 --> 01:11:06.640
You could do this with
a pen if you wanted.

01:11:06.640 --> 01:11:07.990
You could do this.

01:11:07.990 --> 01:11:10.040
Someone else could hold a
wand, and you could do that,

01:11:10.040 --> 01:11:11.580
if you've got someone
that can do that for you.

01:11:11.580 --> 01:11:13.310
Practice accommodation for a few minutes,

01:11:13.310 --> 01:11:14.850
maybe every other day,

01:11:14.850 --> 01:11:16.410
just bringing something in close.

01:11:16.410 --> 01:11:18.183
You'll feel the strain
of your eyes doing that.

01:11:18.183 --> 01:11:21.010
I can feel it right now, move it out.

01:11:21.010 --> 01:11:22.550
You'll feel a relaxation point.

01:11:22.550 --> 01:11:24.240
Move it past that relaxation point,

01:11:24.240 --> 01:11:25.073
where you will have to do

01:11:25.073 --> 01:11:26.240
what's called the vergence eye movement

01:11:26.240 --> 01:11:28.670
to maintain focus on that
location as it moves out,

01:11:28.670 --> 01:11:30.100
bring it back in.

01:11:30.100 --> 01:11:32.760
At the point where you
actually have to go cross-eyed,

01:11:32.760 --> 01:11:33.980
this will differ for different people,

01:11:33.980 --> 01:11:35.870
depending on how far apart your eyes are,

01:11:35.870 --> 01:11:37.580
so called interpupillary distance.

01:11:37.580 --> 01:11:39.330
So for me, I have been teased before,

01:11:39.330 --> 01:11:41.520
I have a very short
interpupillary distance.

01:11:41.520 --> 01:11:44.340
I'm not a cyclops, but I'm heading there.

01:11:44.340 --> 01:11:47.070
Some people are more
walleyed, like a flounder.

01:11:47.070 --> 01:11:49.860
Well, depending on your
interpupillary distance,

01:11:49.860 --> 01:11:50.890
the point at which things

01:11:50.890 --> 01:11:53.910
get blurry and cross-eyed will vary.

01:11:53.910 --> 01:11:56.640
But for me, you know, as I get about,

01:11:56.640 --> 01:11:59.390
oh gosh, I guess it's about
six inches from my nose.

01:11:59.390 --> 01:12:01.470
It's really hard, I can't
accommodate any longer.

01:12:01.470 --> 01:12:04.030
I move it out another inch,
and everything's in nice focus.

01:12:04.030 --> 01:12:05.970
Try and see whether or not
you can get things closer.

01:12:05.970 --> 01:12:07.340
Now, you don't want to get cross-eyed.

01:12:07.340 --> 01:12:09.040
Remember what your parents told you,

01:12:09.040 --> 01:12:10.100
or my parents told me,

01:12:10.100 --> 01:12:12.350
that if you cross your
eyes, when you're young,

01:12:12.350 --> 01:12:13.550
that they can stay that way.

01:12:13.550 --> 01:12:16.080
Actually, they won't
necessarily stay that way,

01:12:16.080 --> 01:12:18.980
but your brain can
start losing information

01:12:18.980 --> 01:12:21.850
and the ability to see binocular depth,

01:12:21.850 --> 01:12:22.990
something we'll talk about in a moment.

01:12:22.990 --> 01:12:25.360
But for now, the protocol would be,

01:12:25.360 --> 01:12:27.470
you know, two to three,
maybe five minutes,

01:12:27.470 --> 01:12:29.440
just practice that,
practice accommodation,

01:12:29.440 --> 01:12:31.910
and then be sure to give
your eyes some rest,

01:12:31.910 --> 01:12:34.550
get outside, look at a
horizon, or do nothing,

01:12:34.550 --> 01:12:36.300
just kind of let your eyes go soft.

01:12:36.300 --> 01:12:38.140
I guess what the yogis
would call soft gaze.

01:12:38.140 --> 01:12:41.230
Just kind of relax your eyelids,
not this, not eyes closed.

01:12:41.230 --> 01:12:43.870
Just relaxed, panoramic vision,

01:12:43.870 --> 01:12:46.950
try and see the walls around
you without moving your head.

01:12:46.950 --> 01:12:48.330
Exercise your eye muscles,

01:12:48.330 --> 01:12:50.970
exercise the accommodation
mechanisms of your eyes,

01:12:50.970 --> 01:12:53.190
practice a little bit of smooth pursuit.

01:12:53.190 --> 01:12:54.630
You don't have to be neurotic about this,

01:12:54.630 --> 01:12:58.250
but if you do this often
enough, meaning every other day,

01:12:58.250 --> 01:13:00.740
every third day or so, you
can be the strange person

01:13:00.740 --> 01:13:02.770
on the plane or in the
classroom doing this.

01:13:02.770 --> 01:13:05.320
You know, that people might
chuckle or look at you funny,

01:13:05.320 --> 01:13:06.990
or tease you, but that's okay,

01:13:06.990 --> 01:13:08.810
because you'll be able to see

01:13:08.810 --> 01:13:11.100
when they are losing their vision,

01:13:11.100 --> 01:13:13.050
so you'll get the last laugh.

01:13:13.050 --> 01:13:15.050
Please don't laugh at them,
but maybe you can help them.

01:13:15.050 --> 01:13:17.243
At that point, you can
hold the pen for them.

01:13:18.360 --> 01:13:19.330
It's worth doing.

01:13:19.330 --> 01:13:21.240
It's really worth preserving your vision.

01:13:21.240 --> 01:13:23.630
And again, if you're a
young person, this is great,

01:13:23.630 --> 01:13:24.950
because then you can actually build

01:13:24.950 --> 01:13:27.290
an extra strong visual system,

01:13:27.290 --> 01:13:29.630
using all the tools that we're describing.

01:13:29.630 --> 01:13:33.190
I do want to talk about
a new set of findings

01:13:33.190 --> 01:13:34.960
that are related to red light

01:13:34.960 --> 01:13:38.000
and offsetting age-related
macular degeneration.

01:13:38.000 --> 01:13:39.980
There are a lot of ways
in which our visual system

01:13:39.980 --> 01:13:40.840
gets worse over time,

01:13:40.840 --> 01:13:44.070
but one is so called age-related
macular degeneration.

01:13:44.070 --> 01:13:46.210
Glen Jeffrey at the
University College London,

01:13:46.210 --> 01:13:48.800
somebody I've known for decades as a,

01:13:48.800 --> 01:13:50.340
because he's a scientist,

01:13:50.340 --> 01:13:52.450
has done beautiful work on
development and function

01:13:52.450 --> 01:13:53.283
of the visual system,

01:13:53.283 --> 01:13:55.760
has published a number of papers recently,

01:13:55.760 --> 01:13:59.050
one that got a particularly high amount

01:13:59.050 --> 01:14:00.140
of attention in the press

01:14:00.140 --> 01:14:03.820
was one that showed that
flashing red light into the eyes

01:14:03.820 --> 01:14:07.090
early in the day, not late
in the day, early in the day,

01:14:07.090 --> 01:14:11.220
can help offset some age-related
macular degeneration,

01:14:11.220 --> 01:14:14.160
presumably by enhancing
the mitochondrial function

01:14:14.160 --> 01:14:15.730
in the photoreceptors.

01:14:15.730 --> 01:14:17.950
There does seem to be
some evidence for that.

01:14:17.950 --> 01:14:19.530
Although, it's still early days,

01:14:19.530 --> 01:14:21.820
I want to emphasize
you don't want to shine

01:14:21.820 --> 01:14:23.250
really bright lights into your eyes.

01:14:23.250 --> 01:14:24.580
You never want to look at any light

01:14:24.580 --> 01:14:26.900
that's so bright that it's painful,

01:14:26.900 --> 01:14:28.740
and you never want to force
your eyelids to stay open.

01:14:28.740 --> 01:14:31.020
If you need to close your eyes
in order to be comfortable,

01:14:31.020 --> 01:14:33.420
well, then chances are
that light is too bright.

01:14:33.420 --> 01:14:35.590
But doing just a couple minutes a day,

01:14:35.590 --> 01:14:37.780
like two minutes a day of flashing

01:14:37.780 --> 01:14:40.543
this red light into one
eye, and then the other.

01:14:41.380 --> 01:14:44.440
As long as it was early in
the day before noon time,

01:14:44.440 --> 01:14:46.110
and as long as it was in individuals

01:14:46.110 --> 01:14:48.900
that were 40 years or older,

01:14:48.900 --> 01:14:50.670
did seem to have a significant effect

01:14:50.670 --> 01:14:53.840
in offsetting some of the
age-related macular degeneration

01:14:53.840 --> 01:14:55.620
that would otherwise occur.

01:14:55.620 --> 01:14:56.900
Again, these are early findings.

01:14:56.900 --> 01:14:59.240
If you want to do this, please be careful.

01:14:59.240 --> 01:15:02.640
Please talk to your optometrist
and/or ophthalmologist.

01:15:02.640 --> 01:15:03.700
Your eyesight is precious.

01:15:03.700 --> 01:15:06.150
You don't want to damage
it, but it is interesting.

01:15:06.150 --> 01:15:07.500
And it does seem like red light

01:15:07.500 --> 01:15:09.310
can improve the function
of the mitochondria.

01:15:09.310 --> 01:15:11.870
These photoreceptors have
a lot of mitochondria,

01:15:11.870 --> 01:15:14.570
the energy-producing
organelles within the cells,

01:15:14.570 --> 01:15:17.740
because they are some of the
most metabolically active cells

01:15:17.740 --> 01:15:18.990
in your entire body.

01:15:18.990 --> 01:15:20.970
Your photoreceptors
are active all the time

01:15:20.970 --> 01:15:21.803
as you're looking around,

01:15:21.803 --> 01:15:23.870
and even when your eyes
are closed, they're active.

01:15:23.870 --> 01:15:26.460
In fact, through a weird
twist of the biology,

01:15:26.460 --> 01:15:29.130
and please look this up if
you're really interested in this,

01:15:29.130 --> 01:15:32.580
your photoreceptors are actually
most active in the dark.

01:15:32.580 --> 01:15:33.413
This is so weird.

01:15:33.413 --> 01:15:37.100
It's a twist of biology, the
way the system's arranged,

01:15:37.100 --> 01:15:40.150
that when light comes on,
they shut off their activity.

01:15:40.150 --> 01:15:42.300
So actually whether or
not you see something

01:15:42.300 --> 01:15:44.880
in front of you, like this pen or my face,

01:15:44.880 --> 01:15:47.350
is because the way your photoreceptors

01:15:47.350 --> 01:15:49.090
are turning off not turning on.

01:15:49.090 --> 01:15:50.280
It's a really cool twist,

01:15:50.280 --> 01:15:53.580
and I don't want to go too
far down that rabbit hole,

01:15:53.580 --> 01:15:55.150
but check it out if you're interested

01:15:55.150 --> 01:15:56.170
in how photoreceptors work.

01:15:56.170 --> 01:15:59.040
It's an absolutely incredible literature.

01:15:59.040 --> 01:16:01.680
Just Google, excuse
me, look up on the web.

01:16:01.680 --> 01:16:03.020
We are not partial just to Google.

01:16:03.020 --> 01:16:06.070
I happen to use Google,
but use your web browser

01:16:06.070 --> 01:16:10.300
to look up photoreceptors
hyperpolarization site.

01:16:10.300 --> 01:16:11.500
And you can learn a lot about that,

01:16:11.500 --> 01:16:14.190
if you're a real nerd for
this stuff, like I am.

01:16:14.190 --> 01:16:17.500
Okay, so red light to the eye,

01:16:17.500 --> 01:16:21.100
can perhaps, it seems,
help maintain vision,

01:16:21.100 --> 01:16:22.770
doing smooth pursuit exercises,

01:16:22.770 --> 01:16:25.370
and accommodation near-far exercises.

01:16:25.370 --> 01:16:27.890
Some people suffer from poor eyesight,

01:16:27.890 --> 01:16:29.800
simply because their eyes get dry.

01:16:29.800 --> 01:16:31.970
There are incredible, believe it or not,

01:16:31.970 --> 01:16:34.410
lubricating mechanisms for the eye,

01:16:34.410 --> 01:16:37.250
not just tears, but a thin sheet of oil.

01:16:37.250 --> 01:16:38.083
I mean, it's just amazing.

01:16:38.083 --> 01:16:40.030
Unless you have some
sort of corneal abrasion,

01:16:40.030 --> 01:16:42.730
the cornea is the clear stuff
on the outside of your eye,

01:16:42.730 --> 01:16:46.010
corneal abrasion, when
you blink, it's smooth,

01:16:46.010 --> 01:16:47.250
you don't feel it.

01:16:47.250 --> 01:16:48.700
It's just really, really smooth.

01:16:48.700 --> 01:16:50.920
And yet, if you've ever
had a corneal scratch,

01:16:50.920 --> 01:16:54.110
I've had this, it's really
rough, it is so painful.

01:16:54.110 --> 01:16:56.613
You have a ton of pain
receptors in the cornea.

01:16:58.840 --> 01:17:03.820
The lubrication of the cornea
is supported by blinking.

01:17:03.820 --> 01:17:06.090
And while it seems a little silly,

01:17:06.090 --> 01:17:09.740
some people actually
benefit from doing some,

01:17:09.740 --> 01:17:12.430
you know, five or 10 or
15 seconds of blinking,

01:17:12.430 --> 01:17:15.040
and then doing their focused work.

01:17:15.040 --> 01:17:16.510
Some people, their eyes are drying out,

01:17:16.510 --> 01:17:19.110
because as we focus, if
we're trying to do something,

01:17:19.110 --> 01:17:22.130
our eyelids stay open,
the eyes can dry out,

01:17:22.130 --> 01:17:23.760
but it also can make it such,

01:17:23.760 --> 01:17:25.430
that when we blink the next time,

01:17:25.430 --> 01:17:26.960
there's a kind of a need to focus,

01:17:26.960 --> 01:17:30.060
because there's some distortions
in these oils and liquids

01:17:30.060 --> 01:17:32.060
across the corneal surface.

01:17:32.060 --> 01:17:33.760
If you're somebody who
suffers from dry eye,

01:17:33.760 --> 01:17:35.310
I do hope they'll find a treatment

01:17:35.310 --> 01:17:36.440
or a cure for dry eye soon.

01:17:36.440 --> 01:17:37.910
There isn't one at present.

01:17:37.910 --> 01:17:39.640
Someone stands to make
a lot of money out there

01:17:39.640 --> 01:17:42.194
if you can find a cure for dry eye.

01:17:42.194 --> 01:17:45.020
Let the companies know or start a company,

01:17:45.020 --> 01:17:47.140
right now it's still a
mystery as to how to do that.

01:17:47.140 --> 01:17:49.120
But blinking for five 15 seconds,

01:17:49.120 --> 01:17:51.520
probably slowly, not as quickly
as I'm doing here on video,

01:17:51.520 --> 01:17:54.370
but just, you know, maybe a
blink every a second or two

01:17:54.370 --> 01:17:56.410
for 15 seconds can lubricate the eyes.

01:17:56.410 --> 01:17:59.340
And that's not directly
related to anything neural,

01:17:59.340 --> 01:18:01.620
it's just going to allow the
optics of your eye to be clear.

01:18:01.620 --> 01:18:03.980
Just like when the screen
of your phone gets dirty,

01:18:03.980 --> 01:18:05.650
like when Costello's texting on my phone,

01:18:05.650 --> 01:18:07.740
and I pick it up, and it's
like covered with smudge,

01:18:07.740 --> 01:18:09.610
to clean it off in order
to see things clearly,

01:18:09.610 --> 01:18:12.090
the same thing is happening
for these optical devices

01:18:12.090 --> 01:18:14.140
on the front of your brain.

01:18:14.140 --> 01:18:16.010
Remember, these are brain.

01:18:16.010 --> 01:18:18.810
Okay, so a lot of protocols today,

01:18:18.810 --> 01:18:22.670
almost all of them behavioral protocols.

01:18:22.670 --> 01:18:25.937
I do want to talk a little
bit more about vision

01:18:25.937 --> 01:18:27.650
and how it works internally.

01:18:27.650 --> 01:18:29.410
And then I also want to talk about

01:18:29.410 --> 01:18:31.260
some of the foods and supplements

01:18:31.260 --> 01:18:32.930
that have been shown to support vision

01:18:32.930 --> 01:18:34.440
and offset visual loss,

01:18:34.440 --> 01:18:36.970
and maybe even reverse some visual loss.

01:18:36.970 --> 01:18:40.143
Let's talk about binocular
vision and lazy eye.

01:18:41.050 --> 01:18:42.670
I'm very familiar with lazy eye,

01:18:42.670 --> 01:18:46.290
because when I was a kid,
I went swimming one day,

01:18:46.290 --> 01:18:49.330
one day, and I didn't have my goggles.

01:18:49.330 --> 01:18:51.620
And so, something must
have been happening,

01:18:51.620 --> 01:18:54.920
as I recall, with the eye
moving down through the water,

01:18:54.920 --> 01:18:56.010
I've always had this problem

01:18:56.010 --> 01:18:58.620
that I can only do the freestyle
stroke off to one side.

01:18:58.620 --> 01:19:00.290
The people I swim with
are always laughing.

01:19:00.290 --> 01:19:02.430
Somehow, I kind of move toward drowning

01:19:02.430 --> 01:19:04.340
when I try and breathe on the right side.

01:19:04.340 --> 01:19:07.450
I think there's some asymmetry
in the way I'm organized.

01:19:07.450 --> 01:19:09.820
Anyway, I was off to my left,

01:19:09.820 --> 01:19:12.280
and my eye kept going
in and out of the water,

01:19:12.280 --> 01:19:13.450
and there was chlorine in the water,

01:19:13.450 --> 01:19:14.500
and it was making my own uncomfortable,

01:19:14.500 --> 01:19:15.603
so I just closed my eye.

01:19:15.603 --> 01:19:16.520
I just decided, you know,

01:19:16.520 --> 01:19:19.053
I knew more or less how
to swim straight-ish.

01:19:19.890 --> 01:19:21.680
Might've bounced off the
lane lines a few times,

01:19:21.680 --> 01:19:23.290
but I just use the other
eye to kind of steer

01:19:23.290 --> 01:19:25.140
for that mark on the wall.

01:19:25.140 --> 01:19:28.810
Got out of the pool,
took a shower, dried off,

01:19:28.810 --> 01:19:32.580
and then completely lost by
binocular vision for three days,

01:19:32.580 --> 01:19:33.413
completely.

01:19:34.260 --> 01:19:37.150
The young brain, up until about age seven,

01:19:37.150 --> 01:19:40.300
but maybe even extending
out until about age 12

01:19:40.300 --> 01:19:44.260
is extremely vulnerable to differences

01:19:44.260 --> 01:19:46.890
in ocular input between the two eyes.

01:19:46.890 --> 01:19:49.530
My scientific great-grandparents
won the Nobel Prize

01:19:49.530 --> 01:19:51.670
for discovering so
called critical periods,

01:19:51.670 --> 01:19:54.010
periods of time in which
the brain is more plastic,

01:19:54.010 --> 01:19:55.530
more able to change.

01:19:55.530 --> 01:19:57.910
Those two guys, David
Hubel and Torsten Wiesel,

01:19:57.910 --> 01:19:59.110
thank you, David and Torsten,

01:19:59.110 --> 01:20:01.530
forever changed the face
of visual neuroscience

01:20:01.530 --> 01:20:02.860
and forever changed the way

01:20:02.860 --> 01:20:06.780
we think about treatment
of the young brain.

01:20:06.780 --> 01:20:08.350
It used to be thought that
you wouldn't want to do

01:20:08.350 --> 01:20:10.210
a surgery on a young kid,

01:20:10.210 --> 01:20:13.900
because of risk of anesthesia
in young individuals.

01:20:13.900 --> 01:20:17.020
But we now know that you need
to repair these imbalances,

01:20:17.020 --> 01:20:19.030
that even a few hours,

01:20:19.030 --> 01:20:21.040
okay, I don't want to scare
anybody, I'll talk about reversal.

01:20:21.040 --> 01:20:24.550
But a few hours of occluding
one eye early in life

01:20:24.550 --> 01:20:27.710
can lead to permanent,
unless something's done,

01:20:27.710 --> 01:20:28.920
permanent changes in the way

01:20:28.920 --> 01:20:31.330
that the brain perceives
the outside world,

01:20:31.330 --> 01:20:33.870
such that when that
eye is opened up again,

01:20:33.870 --> 01:20:35.460
the brain actually can't make sense

01:20:35.460 --> 01:20:36.440
of anything that's coming through it.

01:20:36.440 --> 01:20:38.630
It shuts down that visual pathway somehow.

01:20:38.630 --> 01:20:39.950
So what happened to me was,

01:20:39.950 --> 01:20:42.360
I actually was, my eye was fine.

01:20:42.360 --> 01:20:43.860
I got out of the pool, I opened my eye,

01:20:43.860 --> 01:20:45.450
but I couldn't see through that eye.

01:20:45.450 --> 01:20:47.400
Everything was blurry, double vision,

01:20:47.400 --> 01:20:48.770
unless I covered this eye,

01:20:48.770 --> 01:20:50.840
and then I could see perfectly fine.

01:20:50.840 --> 01:20:53.230
Fortunately, I went to an ophthalmologist

01:20:53.230 --> 01:20:55.240
who understood the literature.

01:20:55.240 --> 01:20:57.710
Thank you, Dr. Mark Lurie,

01:20:57.710 --> 01:21:02.530
who understood the
literature and made it clear

01:21:02.530 --> 01:21:05.700
that what I needed to do was
to occlude the other eye,

01:21:05.700 --> 01:21:07.500
the eye that was working very well.

01:21:07.500 --> 01:21:09.360
Clearly, he understood the
work of you Huber and Wiesel.

01:21:09.360 --> 01:21:11.200
Now, again, you don't want
to start playing games

01:21:11.200 --> 01:21:12.540
with this kind of stuff when you're a kid.

01:21:12.540 --> 01:21:14.850
If you wear, let's say you
have a Halloween costume

01:21:14.850 --> 01:21:15.960
and you wear an eye patch,

01:21:15.960 --> 01:21:18.000
you're a pirate or
something for Halloween,

01:21:18.000 --> 01:21:19.870
and you cover it up on one side,

01:21:19.870 --> 01:21:21.670
probably for the night
of Halloween, it's okay.

01:21:21.670 --> 01:21:25.150
I do not recommend doing
that recreationally

01:21:25.150 --> 01:21:27.210
if you don't need that
if you're a young child

01:21:27.210 --> 01:21:28.180
or for your child to do that.

01:21:28.180 --> 01:21:31.080
Because, indeed, you create imbalances

01:21:31.080 --> 01:21:33.750
in the brain machinery
that compares information

01:21:33.750 --> 01:21:34.910
coming in through the two eyes,

01:21:34.910 --> 01:21:38.020
and it can shut down
the neural information

01:21:38.020 --> 01:21:40.440
for the occluded, the closed eye.

01:21:40.440 --> 01:21:42.280
Now, I was able to reverse this issue,

01:21:42.280 --> 01:21:44.250
but my binocular vision
has never been terrific.

01:21:44.250 --> 01:21:45.770
I'm much better at the dart board

01:21:45.770 --> 01:21:48.160
and still not very good
if I close one eye.

01:21:48.160 --> 01:21:49.440
I'm much better at the pool table,

01:21:49.440 --> 01:21:52.320
if I close one eye, and
I still am terrible.

01:21:52.320 --> 01:21:55.740
I was the kid in, you
know, in the outfield.

01:21:55.740 --> 01:21:56.840
You know, the ball is coming towards me,

01:21:56.840 --> 01:21:58.210
the ball's coming towards me,
I'm going to catch the ball,

01:21:58.210 --> 01:22:00.540
and like it hit me square in the lip.

01:22:00.540 --> 01:22:03.020
My binocular vision isn't great

01:22:03.020 --> 01:22:05.780
as a consequence of this early event.

01:22:05.780 --> 01:22:09.960
And I have a hard time with
those binocular stereograms,

01:22:09.960 --> 01:22:11.190
those images that are kind of,

01:22:11.190 --> 01:22:12.250
you're supposed to look at them,

01:22:12.250 --> 01:22:15.510
and then the binocular
depth image like pops out.

01:22:15.510 --> 01:22:16.490
All the other kids were going,

01:22:16.490 --> 01:22:18.670
oh, there's the, whatever,
the Statue of Liberty.

01:22:18.670 --> 01:22:21.080
There's the [inaudible], and I see dots.

01:22:21.080 --> 01:22:24.630
Okay, so I have binocular
vision, but I use other cues.

01:22:24.630 --> 01:22:27.430
I use the near-far cues
that I talked about before.

01:22:27.430 --> 01:22:29.750
Motion parallax, the fact
that things are closer to me

01:22:29.750 --> 01:22:32.050
are moving faster than
things further away,

01:22:32.050 --> 01:22:33.780
in order to judge depth.

01:22:33.780 --> 01:22:35.530
And years later, when I got involved in,

01:22:35.530 --> 01:22:37.580
and I don't suggest this for most people,

01:22:39.160 --> 01:22:40.860
I got involved in boxing and martial arts

01:22:40.860 --> 01:22:41.730
when I was younger.

01:22:41.730 --> 01:22:43.480
You sometimes will see fighters,

01:22:43.480 --> 01:22:46.100
this is a slip to avoid getting punched.

01:22:46.100 --> 01:22:48.320
It's also generating motion parallax.

01:22:48.320 --> 01:22:52.690
Many animals judge depth
by moving their head,

01:22:52.690 --> 01:22:56.400
not by using other mechanisms
of accommodation, okay?

01:22:56.400 --> 01:22:59.220
So a lot of birds and monkeys and animals

01:22:59.220 --> 01:23:02.620
will judge depth by moving
their head like this,

01:23:02.620 --> 01:23:04.540
or they'll move from side to side.

01:23:04.540 --> 01:23:06.450
Animals that will undulate sometimes

01:23:06.450 --> 01:23:08.360
are actually doing a depth measurement,

01:23:08.360 --> 01:23:10.090
because as you move from side to side,

01:23:10.090 --> 01:23:12.540
the brain is able to do the math of depth.

01:23:12.540 --> 01:23:14.380
So what does this all mean
in terms of protocols?

01:23:14.380 --> 01:23:15.330
If you're a young person,

01:23:15.330 --> 01:23:18.590
do your best to get really
good binocular vision,

01:23:18.590 --> 01:23:21.020
not just at level of your
phone or your tablet,

01:23:21.020 --> 01:23:22.100
but also at distance,

01:23:22.100 --> 01:23:25.710
you will build strong
binocular visual machinery

01:23:25.710 --> 01:23:27.867
in the brain and at the level of the eyes

01:23:27.867 --> 01:23:30.110
and the eye musculature.

01:23:30.110 --> 01:23:32.820
Now, if you're somebody
who did have an occlusion,

01:23:32.820 --> 01:23:35.170
what's needed is to cover up the other eye

01:23:35.170 --> 01:23:37.050
to create an imbalance,
so that the weak eye,

01:23:37.050 --> 01:23:37.883
the so-called lazy eye,

01:23:37.883 --> 01:23:40.410
this is sometimes
referred to as amblyopia,

01:23:40.410 --> 01:23:42.090
that eye has to work harder.

01:23:42.090 --> 01:23:45.130
So for me, they patched this other eye

01:23:45.130 --> 01:23:46.260
and made this eye,

01:23:46.260 --> 01:23:47.760
eventually, I got vision
through that eye back.

01:23:47.760 --> 01:23:49.140
then they opened them both up.

01:23:49.140 --> 01:23:50.840
Now, you might ask,

01:23:50.840 --> 01:23:53.330
what happens if you cover
both eyes early in life?

01:23:53.330 --> 01:23:54.720
And this is where it gets interesting.

01:23:54.720 --> 01:23:56.280
You might think, well, if covering one eye

01:23:56.280 --> 01:24:00.430
leads to poor vision for that
eye after that eye is open,

01:24:00.430 --> 01:24:03.110
covering both eyes will
probably make you blind, right?

01:24:03.110 --> 01:24:05.130
Actually, that's not what happens.

01:24:05.130 --> 01:24:06.380
What Hubel and Wiesel discovered

01:24:06.380 --> 01:24:09.820
and what's been affirmed
many, many more times over

01:24:09.820 --> 01:24:13.210
in subsequent studies is
that it's competitive,

01:24:13.210 --> 01:24:14.930
that the two eyes are competing

01:24:14.930 --> 01:24:16.510
for real estate up in the brain.

01:24:16.510 --> 01:24:18.790
So if you actually cover both eyes,

01:24:18.790 --> 01:24:23.090
you actually extend the
period of critical plasticity.

01:24:23.090 --> 01:24:24.710
This is a really interesting aspect

01:24:24.710 --> 01:24:26.890
that other people are
starting to leverage now,

01:24:26.890 --> 01:24:29.480
in terms of how to reopen
plasticity later in life.

01:24:29.480 --> 01:24:30.790
But please don't, you know,

01:24:30.790 --> 01:24:33.080
go around with your eyes
covered for too long.

01:24:33.080 --> 01:24:35.130
There are some like retreats and stuff

01:24:35.130 --> 01:24:38.150
where people go into caves
with absolutely no vision.

01:24:38.150 --> 01:24:39.330
It creates hallucinations.

01:24:39.330 --> 01:24:41.470
We'll talk about why
that is in just a moment,

01:24:41.470 --> 01:24:43.130
but here's my suggestion.

01:24:43.130 --> 01:24:45.490
Try and get balanced visual
input through the two eyes.

01:24:45.490 --> 01:24:47.810
Almost everybody has a dominant eye.

01:24:47.810 --> 01:24:50.330
It usually doesn't relate
to your dominant hand,

01:24:50.330 --> 01:24:51.420
although it can.

01:24:51.420 --> 01:24:53.950
And so for me, if I cover up my right eye,

01:24:53.950 --> 01:24:57.000
I see much less well, much more poorly.

01:24:57.000 --> 01:24:58.210
It's a little bit fuzzy,

01:24:58.210 --> 01:24:59.470
and I have to work harder

01:24:59.470 --> 01:25:01.560
in order to see the camera for instance.

01:25:01.560 --> 01:25:03.220
Then, if I cover up my left eye,

01:25:03.220 --> 01:25:04.910
it's actually really easy for me to relax.

01:25:04.910 --> 01:25:06.920
I have a dominant eye.

01:25:06.920 --> 01:25:08.250
Now, you can balance that out

01:25:08.250 --> 01:25:10.950
by covering up the dominant
eye a little bit each day,

01:25:10.950 --> 01:25:12.940
but I would warn any young people,

01:25:12.940 --> 01:25:16.000
meaning, you know, 12 or younger,

01:25:16.000 --> 01:25:18.130
against creating these imbalances

01:25:18.130 --> 01:25:20.410
if there isn't a clinical need to do that.

01:25:20.410 --> 01:25:23.740
And if you do have strong
imbalances between the two eyes,

01:25:23.740 --> 01:25:27.530
which can be caused by
cataract and lens issues,

01:25:27.530 --> 01:25:29.940
can be caused by neuromuscular
issues, et cetera,

01:25:29.940 --> 01:25:32.720
to try and get those dealt
with as early as possible

01:25:32.720 --> 01:25:35.410
by contacting a really
good ophthalmologist

01:25:35.410 --> 01:25:37.700
and ideally a neuro-ophthalmologist.

01:25:37.700 --> 01:25:39.230
It is very normal,

01:25:39.230 --> 01:25:42.620
I should say, it's very common
for young children, babies

01:25:42.620 --> 01:25:45.390
to have an eye that, with strabismus,

01:25:45.390 --> 01:25:48.020
that either deviates
out or that deviates in.

01:25:48.020 --> 01:25:50.180
It is important to correct that.

01:25:50.180 --> 01:25:53.220
If you would like to
have balanced division

01:25:53.220 --> 01:25:54.530
between the two eyes and for the brain

01:25:54.530 --> 01:25:57.410
to respond equally to the two eyes

01:25:57.410 --> 01:26:01.480
and to have, I would say high
fidelity, quality vision.

01:26:01.480 --> 01:26:03.890
Although some people who
have an eye that drifts

01:26:03.890 --> 01:26:06.610
can function normally in life,

01:26:06.610 --> 01:26:09.260
you have an opportunity
early in life to rescue that.

01:26:10.210 --> 01:26:11.770
I won't do, well, maybe I will do this,

01:26:11.770 --> 01:26:14.520
but I can actually relax this eye.

01:26:14.520 --> 01:26:16.160
It's so weak, in some cases,

01:26:16.160 --> 01:26:17.500
that it actually can start to deviate.

01:26:17.500 --> 01:26:18.410
Here, I'll just do this here.

01:26:18.410 --> 01:26:19.243
It's not crossing my eyes.

01:26:19.243 --> 01:26:22.310
So I actually can move my,
I can misalign my eyes,

01:26:22.310 --> 01:26:23.960
because I have to fight very hard

01:26:23.960 --> 01:26:25.810
to have the musculature for this eye,

01:26:26.765 --> 01:26:28.770
keep that eye aligned with the other eye.

01:26:28.770 --> 01:26:30.980
And that's because I've
been doing eye exercises,

01:26:30.980 --> 01:26:32.390
since I was in my twenties,

01:26:32.390 --> 01:26:34.270
'cause I noticed when I would study a lot,

01:26:34.270 --> 01:26:36.280
this eye would start to drift
in, I'd start to see double,

01:26:36.280 --> 01:26:37.240
and I would then, next thing you know,

01:26:37.240 --> 01:26:38.317
I was just covering the eye up,

01:26:38.317 --> 01:26:39.920
and it was getting weaker and weaker,

01:26:39.920 --> 01:26:41.810
just like the atrophy of a muscle.

01:26:41.810 --> 01:26:43.740
So I went to the doctor, what did they do?

01:26:43.740 --> 01:26:45.660
They did the exact wrong thing.

01:26:45.660 --> 01:26:47.860
The optometrist I went to gave me a prism,

01:26:47.860 --> 01:26:50.070
which adjusted it so that I
could see things normally,

01:26:50.070 --> 01:26:51.790
which just made the eye weaker and weaker.

01:26:51.790 --> 01:26:54.640
It's like putting a weak arm into a sling.

01:26:54.640 --> 01:26:58.750
So I had to spend at least
three years of 10 minutes a day,

01:26:58.750 --> 01:27:01.830
is what I recommend, doing near-far,

01:27:01.830 --> 01:27:05.940
covering up my good eye, doing
near-far with my bad eye.

01:27:05.940 --> 01:27:09.410
And now, it's been about 10, 12 years

01:27:09.410 --> 01:27:12.490
that I have pretty
decent binocular vision.

01:27:12.490 --> 01:27:15.400
Now, many of you aren't dealing with this,

01:27:15.400 --> 01:27:17.450
or have these early childhood issues.

01:27:17.450 --> 01:27:19.680
Some of you might be experiencing

01:27:19.680 --> 01:27:22.100
challenges with fatigued eyes

01:27:22.100 --> 01:27:24.300
or with differences in
focus with the two eyes.

01:27:24.300 --> 01:27:26.870
These eye exercises of
near-far, smooth pursuit,

01:27:26.870 --> 01:27:30.010
and checking for dominant
and non-dominant eye

01:27:30.010 --> 01:27:31.460
can be very beneficial.

01:27:31.460 --> 01:27:34.150
I'm again, I'm not a
clinician, so I don't want to,

01:27:34.150 --> 01:27:35.780
you know, give you protocols

01:27:35.780 --> 01:27:37.420
or enforce protocols on anybody.

01:27:37.420 --> 01:27:39.360
You need to figure out what's
right and safe for you,

01:27:39.360 --> 01:27:42.090
given your vision history.

01:27:42.090 --> 01:27:44.390
I do recommend talking to a
really good ophthalmologist

01:27:44.390 --> 01:27:46.690
if you have severe vision
problems of any kind,

01:27:46.690 --> 01:27:49.800
or if you want to offset
vision problems of any kind.

01:27:49.800 --> 01:27:51.210
An optometrist as well,

01:27:51.210 --> 01:27:53.960
but ideally would be a
neuro-ophthalmologist.

01:27:53.960 --> 01:27:56.630
Okay, I did mention hallucinations,

01:27:56.630 --> 01:27:58.697
and they're fun to talk
about and think about.

01:27:58.697 --> 01:28:00.510
And for years, people have asked,

01:28:00.510 --> 01:28:03.320
why do people get visual hallucinations.

01:28:03.320 --> 01:28:04.660
Costello's in sleep right now,

01:28:04.660 --> 01:28:06.720
you can probably hear him
snoring, he's snoring so loud.

01:28:06.720 --> 01:28:07.910
He's probably having hallucinations

01:28:07.910 --> 01:28:11.660
about rabbits, pizza, and
those are mainly his favorite,

01:28:11.660 --> 01:28:12.493
and sleep.

01:28:12.493 --> 01:28:14.413
He's dreaming about sleep in sleep.

01:28:15.450 --> 01:28:18.480
Hallucinations are a property
of the visual system,

01:28:18.480 --> 01:28:21.970
and it was always thought
that hallucinations arise,

01:28:21.970 --> 01:28:24.310
because of over-activation or activation

01:28:24.310 --> 01:28:25.860
of certain aspects of the visual system.

01:28:25.860 --> 01:28:27.450
I just briefly want to mention a paper

01:28:27.450 --> 01:28:28.770
that was published by my good friend

01:28:28.770 --> 01:28:33.070
and phenomenal scientist and
physicist for that matter,

01:28:33.070 --> 01:28:36.630
Cris Niell who's up at the
University of Oregon in Eugene.

01:28:36.630 --> 01:28:38.970
They studied LSD light compounds

01:28:38.970 --> 01:28:42.290
and discovered that
hallucinations actually occur,

01:28:42.290 --> 01:28:46.230
because portions of your
brain become underactive.

01:28:46.230 --> 01:28:49.050
The visual portions of your
brain are under-stimulated.

01:28:49.050 --> 01:28:50.520
This is probably why,

01:28:50.520 --> 01:28:52.580
when people go into these cave retreats,

01:28:52.580 --> 01:28:55.220
something I've never done, I
don't think I ever will do,

01:28:55.220 --> 01:28:56.800
where it's completely black,

01:28:56.800 --> 01:28:58.930
pretty soon, they start hallucinating.

01:28:58.930 --> 01:29:01.910
They start seeing things, even
though there's nothing there.

01:29:01.910 --> 01:29:04.160
The visual system is desperate

01:29:04.160 --> 01:29:06.050
to make guesses about
what's out in the world.

01:29:06.050 --> 01:29:07.570
It's like the eager beaver of your brain.

01:29:07.570 --> 01:29:08.660
It's like, what's out
there, what's out there,

01:29:08.660 --> 01:29:10.270
what's out there?

01:29:10.270 --> 01:29:13.003
Even in low to no vision
people, blind people,

01:29:13.860 --> 01:29:15.580
they are, their brain is
going to be making guesses

01:29:15.580 --> 01:29:17.210
about what's out there
in the auditory world.

01:29:17.210 --> 01:29:20.780
What sounds are there? What
touch sensations are there?

01:29:20.780 --> 01:29:23.430
For sighted folks, it's going to be,

01:29:23.430 --> 01:29:24.970
what's out there in terms of light?

01:29:24.970 --> 01:29:26.190
Light is the dominant way.

01:29:26.190 --> 01:29:27.210
Vision is the dominant way

01:29:27.210 --> 01:29:29.270
that we evaluate the world around us.

01:29:29.270 --> 01:29:31.780
So it turns out that hallucinations

01:29:31.780 --> 01:29:34.250
are an under-activation
of the visual system,

01:29:34.250 --> 01:29:36.880
and then a compensatory, a compensation,

01:29:36.880 --> 01:29:38.010
by which the visual system

01:29:38.010 --> 01:29:41.060
creates activity and hallucinations.

01:29:41.060 --> 01:29:42.680
So if you're in the dark long enough,

01:29:42.680 --> 01:29:44.710
you start to hallucinate and see things.

01:29:44.710 --> 01:29:47.710
So, that's a little note
about hallucinations.

01:29:47.710 --> 01:29:49.890
One of the things that you
can do to improve your vision,

01:29:49.890 --> 01:29:51.540
and it's also kind of fun

01:29:51.540 --> 01:29:55.000
is to put a Snellen chart in your home.

01:29:55.000 --> 01:29:57.010
A Snellen chart is that list of letters.

01:29:57.010 --> 01:29:59.880
Or if you go to the dreaded
Department of Motor Vehicles,

01:29:59.880 --> 01:30:01.160
actually I'm up for renewal soon,

01:30:01.160 --> 01:30:03.610
so I love the Department
of Motor Vehicles.

01:30:03.610 --> 01:30:04.720
The Department of Motor Vehicles,

01:30:04.720 --> 01:30:06.330
they'll have you cover up an eye,

01:30:06.330 --> 01:30:09.470
read the letters on the chart,

01:30:09.470 --> 01:30:11.080
the letters of course
gets smaller and smaller,

01:30:11.080 --> 01:30:13.620
they're trying to figure out
roughly what your vision is.

01:30:13.620 --> 01:30:16.520
Cover up the other eye, you'll do that.

01:30:16.520 --> 01:30:19.620
Some people including nerdy,
vision scientists like me

01:30:19.620 --> 01:30:22.040
have had Snellen charts in their office

01:30:22.040 --> 01:30:24.300
or in their home for many years now,

01:30:24.300 --> 01:30:25.270
and you can just practice,

01:30:25.270 --> 01:30:26.270
and you can see how you're doing

01:30:26.270 --> 01:30:28.630
sitting at a particular distance.

01:30:28.630 --> 01:30:31.240
Your, this is something
that's not often mentioned,

01:30:31.240 --> 01:30:33.080
but your performance on the Snellen chart

01:30:33.080 --> 01:30:36.180
will vary depending on time of day,

01:30:36.180 --> 01:30:38.040
because your level of fatigue

01:30:38.040 --> 01:30:39.930
and your ability to
control that accommodation

01:30:39.930 --> 01:30:42.570
and other mechanisms of
the eye muscles will vary,

01:30:42.570 --> 01:30:44.550
so you can take it as an average.

01:30:44.550 --> 01:30:46.430
It's also a good thing,

01:30:46.430 --> 01:30:48.150
if you're going to get your vision tested

01:30:48.150 --> 01:30:49.744
for corrective lenses,

01:30:49.744 --> 01:30:51.560
or maybe you're going to do laser surgery,

01:30:51.560 --> 01:30:52.610
or something of that sort,

01:30:52.610 --> 01:30:53.810
if you're thinking about any of that,

01:30:53.810 --> 01:30:55.670
to really get it measured
by a professional.

01:30:55.670 --> 01:30:57.906
The ones that you get
in those supermarkets,

01:30:57.906 --> 01:31:01.030
or in many eyeglass stores,

01:31:01.030 --> 01:31:02.260
apologies to the eyeglass stores,

01:31:02.260 --> 01:31:05.473
are often wrong by an order of magnitude.

01:31:06.400 --> 01:31:08.940
And then, when you start
putting corrective lenses on

01:31:08.940 --> 01:31:12.410
that are over-correcting
or under-correcting,

01:31:12.410 --> 01:31:14.240
but more often are over-correcting,

01:31:14.240 --> 01:31:16.220
well, then you're essentially
weakening the system.

01:31:16.220 --> 01:31:17.900
It's like putting a prosthetic on a limb

01:31:17.900 --> 01:31:19.760
that you didn't necessarily need,

01:31:19.760 --> 01:31:22.530
or robot arm when you didn't need

01:31:22.530 --> 01:31:23.650
the use of the robot arm.

01:31:23.650 --> 01:31:25.760
Although now there's so much
excitement about robots,

01:31:25.760 --> 01:31:27.670
I think people are going
to be doing that anyway.

01:31:27.670 --> 01:31:30.090
Nonetheless, get your vision tested

01:31:30.090 --> 01:31:32.130
by somebody who really understands vision,

01:31:32.130 --> 01:31:34.780
like an ophthalmologist or
a really good optometrist.

01:31:35.780 --> 01:31:38.087
If you put a Snellen chart in your home,

01:31:38.087 --> 01:31:41.410
you know, you can do that as
part of your visual training.

01:31:41.410 --> 01:31:43.410
Now, this might seem excessively nerdy,

01:31:43.410 --> 01:31:46.800
but what is more important
than your eyesight, right?

01:31:46.800 --> 01:31:48.050
Eyesight is so vital.

01:31:48.050 --> 01:31:50.730
It's right up there with
movement and our ability to move,

01:31:50.730 --> 01:31:52.410
to generate, to get up out of chairs,

01:31:52.410 --> 01:31:55.280
and to walk and to run, and
to take care of ourselves.

01:31:55.280 --> 01:31:57.910
Eyesight and movement are the main ways

01:31:57.910 --> 01:32:00.660
that we are able to take care of ourselves

01:32:00.660 --> 01:32:01.800
and take care of others.

01:32:01.800 --> 01:32:04.010
When you start having compromised eyesight

01:32:04.010 --> 01:32:06.700
or compromised movement,
people need to take care of us,

01:32:06.700 --> 01:32:08.730
and we become much more challenged

01:32:08.730 --> 01:32:10.360
in moving through our daily life.

01:32:10.360 --> 01:32:11.410
So while it might seem nerdy

01:32:11.410 --> 01:32:13.490
to have a Snellen chart in your home,

01:32:13.490 --> 01:32:16.560
or to do a smooth pursuit
exercise a couple of times a week,

01:32:16.560 --> 01:32:18.190
or to get outside for a few hours a day

01:32:18.190 --> 01:32:20.830
and do your reading or
your laptop work there,

01:32:20.830 --> 01:32:23.270
preserving your eyesight
and preserving your vision

01:32:23.270 --> 01:32:25.680
is one of the most life-enhancing

01:32:25.680 --> 01:32:27.970
or quality of life enhancing
things that you can do.

01:32:27.970 --> 01:32:29.640
And if you're a young person,

01:32:29.640 --> 01:32:32.860
and you can build some of
this into your framework

01:32:32.860 --> 01:32:36.330
of exercise or brain training,
if you want to call it that,

01:32:36.330 --> 01:32:38.690
that can be immensely beneficial
and will really set you up

01:32:38.690 --> 01:32:41.290
to have really good vision
over a long period of time.

01:32:41.290 --> 01:32:42.980
Now, of course, there are genetic factors,

01:32:42.980 --> 01:32:45.330
and there are injury-related factors

01:32:45.330 --> 01:32:48.530
that can compromise eyesight
and our ability to see.

01:32:48.530 --> 01:32:51.640
And, of course, the things
I'm talking about today

01:32:51.640 --> 01:32:53.540
aren't going to solve all those issues,

01:32:53.540 --> 01:32:57.030
but they can have a
tremendous, positive impact

01:32:57.030 --> 01:32:58.920
if you're willing to do
just a little bit of work,

01:32:58.920 --> 01:33:02.710
and none of this is
involving any cost, right?

01:33:02.710 --> 01:33:04.350
It's just time cost.

01:33:04.350 --> 01:33:06.870
So I want, I do want to talk
about a few other things

01:33:06.870 --> 01:33:09.400
that can perhaps improve vision.

01:33:09.400 --> 01:33:11.540
I want to dispel a few myths about stuff

01:33:11.540 --> 01:33:13.570
to take to improve vision.

01:33:13.570 --> 01:33:16.510
And then, I want to just
close by talking about

01:33:16.510 --> 01:33:19.840
how we perceive time using our vision,

01:33:19.840 --> 01:33:21.490
because that will nicely set the stage

01:33:21.490 --> 01:33:24.010
for what we're going to
talk about next episode.

01:33:24.010 --> 01:33:27.580
So now, you understand a lot
about the biology of vision.

01:33:27.580 --> 01:33:29.570
You understand that light
has to arrive at the retina

01:33:29.570 --> 01:33:32.060
and get converted into electrical signals.

01:33:32.060 --> 01:33:36.500
That process requires
things like vitamin A,

01:33:36.500 --> 01:33:38.560
a fat soluble vitamin.

01:33:38.560 --> 01:33:42.100
It requires things like the carotinoids.

01:33:42.100 --> 01:33:46.360
That metabolic cascade,
the biochemical cascade,

01:33:46.360 --> 01:33:47.850
is essential for vision.

01:33:47.850 --> 01:33:49.260
And this is why you've been told

01:33:49.260 --> 01:33:50.930
that carrots help you see better

01:33:50.930 --> 01:33:52.580
'cause they're high in vitamin A.

01:33:53.930 --> 01:33:55.390
There are a few simple things you can do

01:33:55.390 --> 01:33:56.870
to support your vision.

01:33:56.870 --> 01:34:01.870
First of all, it is true
that eating vegetables,

01:34:02.340 --> 01:34:03.890
the dark, leafy vegetables

01:34:03.890 --> 01:34:08.040
and things like carrots that
have vitamin A in abundance,

01:34:08.040 --> 01:34:11.190
and eating them in
close to their raw form,

01:34:11.190 --> 01:34:13.410
so naturally occurring foods

01:34:13.410 --> 01:34:17.380
that contain a lot of
vitamin A in their raw form

01:34:17.380 --> 01:34:19.480
can help support vision.

01:34:19.480 --> 01:34:21.430
Now, does that mean that if you ingest

01:34:21.430 --> 01:34:23.610
super physiological amounts of that stuff,

01:34:23.610 --> 01:34:25.840
that it's going to make your
vision that much better?

01:34:25.840 --> 01:34:29.650
No, but you do need a
threshold level of vitamin A

01:34:29.650 --> 01:34:33.800
in order to see and in order to see well.

01:34:33.800 --> 01:34:36.600
Now, there's a lot of excitement nowadays

01:34:36.600 --> 01:34:39.790
about supplementation to
help support the health

01:34:39.790 --> 01:34:40.810
of the visual system.

01:34:40.810 --> 01:34:43.090
And I'm somebody who's pretty open

01:34:43.090 --> 01:34:45.210
to novel forms of supplementation.

01:34:45.210 --> 01:34:46.250
You've probably gathered that,

01:34:46.250 --> 01:34:48.850
if you've been listening
to this podcast for awhile.

01:34:48.850 --> 01:34:50.830
You have to determine what's safe,

01:34:50.830 --> 01:34:53.300
and economical, and right for you,

01:34:53.300 --> 01:34:55.710
what your risk tolerance is, et cetera.

01:34:55.710 --> 01:34:58.660
But I want to talk about a molecule

01:34:58.660 --> 01:35:01.730
that's in a lot of
supplements to support vision,

01:35:01.730 --> 01:35:05.950
and there are some really good
data on, and that's lutein.

01:35:05.950 --> 01:35:07.640
Now, the study I want to describe

01:35:08.750 --> 01:35:11.340
is actually published in 2016.

01:35:11.340 --> 01:35:13.040
It's from the Journal of Ophthalmology.

01:35:13.040 --> 01:35:15.100
It's a good journal.

01:35:15.100 --> 01:35:16.880
And the title of this paper is,

01:35:16.880 --> 01:35:18.410
it might catch your attention,

01:35:18.410 --> 01:35:22.070
it's "Increased macular
pigment optical density,"

01:35:22.070 --> 01:35:24.110
that just means that macula,

01:35:24.110 --> 01:35:26.950
is an area of the eye for central vision,

01:35:26.950 --> 01:35:28.113
for high acuity vision.

01:35:29.090 --> 01:35:32.817
Pigment density there is
good, you want pigment there.

01:35:32.817 --> 01:35:35.717
"Increase macular pigment optical density

01:35:35.717 --> 01:35:37.010
"and visual acuity,"

01:35:37.010 --> 01:35:40.387
Visual acuity is your ability
to see things in fine detail.

01:35:40.387 --> 01:35:42.680
"Following consumption
of a buttermilk drink

01:35:42.680 --> 01:35:45.710
"containing lutein-enriched egg yolks."

01:35:45.710 --> 01:35:49.200
Remember, raw foods?
Lutein-enriched egg yolks.

01:35:49.200 --> 01:35:50.440
Sounds like a Rocky movie,

01:35:50.440 --> 01:35:52.767
where he would drink the raw egg yolks.

01:35:52.767 --> 01:35:56.200
"A randomized double-blind
placebo controlled trial."

01:35:56.200 --> 01:35:59.500
Now, I'm not suggesting you
go out and eat raw egg yolks.

01:35:59.500 --> 01:36:00.630
There's the risk of salmonella.

01:36:00.630 --> 01:36:01.770
Although, I did hear this,

01:36:01.770 --> 01:36:02.820
someone correct me if I'm wrong,

01:36:02.820 --> 01:36:06.040
but the salmonella is actually
on the outside of the egg,

01:36:06.040 --> 01:36:08.950
not actually in the egg
itself, it's on the shell.

01:36:08.950 --> 01:36:13.330
For reasons that relate to how
that egg got into the world,

01:36:13.330 --> 01:36:15.140
that's where the salmonella lives,

01:36:15.140 --> 01:36:17.350
but I could be wrong about that.

01:36:17.350 --> 01:36:19.750
But raw egg yolks are not something

01:36:19.750 --> 01:36:21.960
that most people want to consume.

01:36:21.960 --> 01:36:23.280
What is this lutein stuff?

01:36:23.280 --> 01:36:27.580
Well, lutein is in the pathway
that relates to vitamin A

01:36:27.580 --> 01:36:32.060
and the formation of the
OPs in the photopigment

01:36:32.060 --> 01:36:33.860
that captures light in
the back of your eye,

01:36:33.860 --> 01:36:37.500
literally absorbs light
pigment in your eye,

01:36:37.500 --> 01:36:39.350
and converts that into electrical signals,

01:36:39.350 --> 01:36:40.570
and allows you to see.

01:36:40.570 --> 01:36:42.380
And there is some evidence,

01:36:42.380 --> 01:36:44.360
I spoke to our chair of ophthalmology,

01:36:44.360 --> 01:36:48.110
there is some evidence through
quality peer-reviewed studies

01:36:48.110 --> 01:36:53.110
that supplementing with
lutein can help offset

01:36:53.480 --> 01:36:56.290
some of the detrimental effects

01:36:56.290 --> 01:36:58.800
of age-related macular degeneration.

01:36:58.800 --> 01:37:03.123
But, I want to emphasize
but, or emphasize however,

01:37:04.690 --> 01:37:07.140
only for individuals with moderate

01:37:07.140 --> 01:37:09.560
to severe macular degeneration.

01:37:09.560 --> 01:37:11.620
For people that have normal vision,

01:37:11.620 --> 01:37:16.620
or with a, just a low-degree
of macular degeneration,

01:37:16.780 --> 01:37:19.330
these studies did not see
a significant improvement

01:37:19.330 --> 01:37:22.020
of vision from supplementing with lutein.

01:37:22.020 --> 01:37:23.020
So, I'm not going to to tell you

01:37:23.020 --> 01:37:24.793
to supplement with lutein or not.

01:37:26.180 --> 01:37:29.480
I don't think any study
is holy, but it does seem

01:37:29.480 --> 01:37:32.650
that if you have moderate to
severe macular degeneration,

01:37:32.650 --> 01:37:33.840
talk to your physician, of course,

01:37:33.840 --> 01:37:35.150
talk to your ophthalmologist,

01:37:35.150 --> 01:37:37.650
I'll always say that, and
I'll say it three times,

01:37:39.190 --> 01:37:42.990
supplementing with lutein
could perhaps support vision

01:37:42.990 --> 01:37:45.040
and offset some vision loss in that case.

01:37:45.040 --> 01:37:47.000
Probably also talk to your ophthalmologist

01:37:47.000 --> 01:37:48.330
or consider the red light therapy

01:37:48.330 --> 01:37:49.750
that I talked about earlier.

01:37:49.750 --> 01:37:51.950
Whereas, if you have normal vision,

01:37:51.950 --> 01:37:55.550
or a low amount of macular degeneration,

01:37:55.550 --> 01:37:57.530
it does not seem, at
least from these studies,

01:37:57.530 --> 01:37:59.760
that lutein had much of an effect.

01:37:59.760 --> 01:38:03.860
Now, I know, and I confess
I'm sort of of the mind

01:38:03.860 --> 01:38:08.860
that if I personally had
age-related macular degeneration,

01:38:09.180 --> 01:38:10.730
or a propensity for it in my family,

01:38:10.730 --> 01:38:15.560
which fortunately I
don't, but in that case,

01:38:15.560 --> 01:38:17.060
I would think that
supplementing with lutein,

01:38:17.060 --> 01:38:20.610
provided it's safe, could
perhaps be of benefit.

01:38:20.610 --> 01:38:22.470
You might want to consider
a low dose of that.

01:38:22.470 --> 01:38:23.840
So again, I'm not pushing any of this

01:38:23.840 --> 01:38:27.910
on anybody by any means,
but you should know that,

01:38:27.910 --> 01:38:30.500
under certain conditions of
severe macular degeneration

01:38:30.500 --> 01:38:31.860
or moderate macular degeneration,

01:38:31.860 --> 01:38:33.430
it does seem like lutein
can be beneficial.

01:38:33.430 --> 01:38:36.090
It does not have to be
consumed through raw egg yolks,

01:38:36.090 --> 01:38:39.900
although that is the
highest density source.

01:38:39.900 --> 01:38:41.670
Cooking the egg yolk, cooking your eggs,

01:38:41.670 --> 01:38:43.490
if you like your scrambled eggs dry,

01:38:43.490 --> 01:38:48.390
or you like your eggs not easy
over or whatever, not runny,

01:38:48.390 --> 01:38:51.030
then you aren't going to get
the benefits of the leucine.

01:38:51.030 --> 01:38:52.430
There are other sources of leucine,

01:38:52.430 --> 01:38:53.920
non-animal sources of leucine as well.

01:38:53.920 --> 01:38:57.030
You can look those up on the internet.

01:38:57.030 --> 01:39:00.830
Now, there are other
compounds that have been shown

01:39:00.830 --> 01:39:03.060
to perhaps be important for offsetting

01:39:03.060 --> 01:39:06.500
or helping different forms of vision loss.

01:39:06.500 --> 01:39:10.880
One is, I'm going to spell
this out, I-D-E-B-E-N-O-N-E,

01:39:10.880 --> 01:39:14.900
idebenone, idebenone, idebenone,

01:39:14.900 --> 01:39:17.433
I can never pronounce these
compounds, forgive me,

01:39:18.370 --> 01:39:20.460
unless I've worked with them.

01:39:20.460 --> 01:39:22.630
There is evidence that
it can be beneficial

01:39:22.630 --> 01:39:27.570
for Leber's congenital eye disease.

01:39:27.570 --> 01:39:30.020
I would definitely go on to examine.com,

01:39:30.020 --> 01:39:32.730
put in I-D-E-B-N-O-N-E.

01:39:32.730 --> 01:39:36.590
And for things like
Leber's optic neuropathies,

01:39:36.590 --> 01:39:39.670
which is a degenerative
condition of the eye,

01:39:39.670 --> 01:39:40.560
whether or not people should

01:39:40.560 --> 01:39:43.270
just be taking this stuff anyway
is still an open question.

01:39:43.270 --> 01:39:45.290
There aren't a lot of studies about it.

01:39:45.290 --> 01:39:46.870
A lot of people that are interested

01:39:46.870 --> 01:39:49.410
in taking things to support their vision

01:39:49.410 --> 01:39:52.193
are taking lutein as a
preventative measure.

01:39:53.380 --> 01:39:55.400
I don't pass any judgment
one way or the other.

01:39:55.400 --> 01:39:57.610
Typically, those supplements

01:39:57.610 --> 01:40:02.550
also include the zeaxanthins
and astaxanthins.

01:40:02.550 --> 01:40:05.670
Okay, the pronunciation of
this is terrible, I'm sure,

01:40:05.670 --> 01:40:07.050
but that's not too far off,

01:40:07.050 --> 01:40:12.050
but basically Z-E-A-X-A-N-T-H-I-N.

01:40:12.830 --> 01:40:13.820
You can see why it's hard to pronounce,

01:40:13.820 --> 01:40:17.020
Z-E-A-X-A-N-T-H-I-N.

01:40:17.020 --> 01:40:21.450
And the other one is
A-S-T-A-X-A-N-T-H-I-N.

01:40:21.450 --> 01:40:24.440
Both of these have been shown, excuse me,

01:40:24.440 --> 01:40:26.180
both of these have been shown

01:40:26.180 --> 01:40:30.860
to offset some of the disruption in vision

01:40:30.860 --> 01:40:32.770
that occurs with aging.

01:40:32.770 --> 01:40:35.320
What is astaxanthin?

01:40:35.320 --> 01:40:37.440
It's a really interesting compound.

01:40:37.440 --> 01:40:41.170
It's the red-pink pigment
found in various seafoods.

01:40:41.170 --> 01:40:43.910
So shrimp, I'm not a big seafood fan,

01:40:43.910 --> 01:40:46.060
but like certain fish, like the,

01:40:46.060 --> 01:40:47.230
you'll see at the fish market

01:40:47.230 --> 01:40:49.510
will have that red-pink pigment.

01:40:49.510 --> 01:40:51.770
And it's also in the
feathers of flamingos,

01:40:51.770 --> 01:40:54.270
please don't eat the
feathers of flamingos,

01:40:54.270 --> 01:40:56.343
and please also don't eat flamingos.

01:40:57.320 --> 01:40:59.520
It's structurally similar to betacarotene,

01:40:59.520 --> 01:41:02.040
so it's very pro vitamin A,

01:41:02.040 --> 01:41:03.710
but it has some chemical differences,

01:41:03.710 --> 01:41:05.900
which may make it safer than vitamin A.

01:41:05.900 --> 01:41:09.210
Remember, vitamin A is
a lipid-soluble vitamin,

01:41:09.210 --> 01:41:12.720
so it can be stored in our
body for long periods of time.

01:41:12.720 --> 01:41:15.360
What is the deal with this astaxanthin?

01:41:15.360 --> 01:41:16.490
You know, what are its drawbacks?

01:41:16.490 --> 01:41:20.790
Well, we can go to our
ever favorite examine.com.

01:41:20.790 --> 01:41:21.623
What does it do?

01:41:21.623 --> 01:41:23.430
Well, it has a number
of different effects,

01:41:23.430 --> 01:41:27.830
a huge number in fact, but it
does seem to notably increase,

01:41:27.830 --> 01:41:29.630
it's now been shown in three studies,

01:41:29.630 --> 01:41:32.850
the antioxidant enzyme profile.

01:41:32.850 --> 01:41:34.870
It has a number of different effects,

01:41:34.870 --> 01:41:36.820
but the most notable for
sake of this episode,

01:41:36.820 --> 01:41:39.170
is the one on ocular blood flow.

01:41:39.170 --> 01:41:41.930
It does seem to increase the
amount of ocular blood flow,

01:41:41.930 --> 01:41:43.720
so the blood supply to the eyes,

01:41:43.720 --> 01:41:46.120
so that makes it an interesting compound.

01:41:46.120 --> 01:41:47.930
It has a number of other effects.

01:41:47.930 --> 01:41:51.800
For whatever reason, it
also has a notable effect,

01:41:51.800 --> 01:41:55.610
several studies have shown
this, on fertility in males.

